<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 3, Marlins 2  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN WINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Pete Harnisch pitched six innings despite a 2-hour,
40-minute rain delay in the second inning, and the Cincinnati Reds
needed just five hits Saturday night to beat the Florida Marlins
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 35,392 was the largest of the season for
Florida. Only about 5,000 fans remained when play resumed after a
thunderstorm, and Marlins starter Jesus Sanchez was taken out of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Harnisch returned to the mound after the long delay and shut
out Florida over the next 4 1-3 innings. He allowed five hits and
one run.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch improved to 6-2 with a 2.88 ERA in 11 starts since
spending eight weeks on the disabled list with weakness in his
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Graves, Cincinnati's fourth pitcher, got the final four
outs for his 22nd save in 26 chances. The Reds won their third in a
row, and the Marlins have lost three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Florida ended a scoreless streak of 23 innings when Mark Kotsay
homered in the first. Preston Wilson's infield single drove in a
run in the eighth, but with runners at first and third, Mike Lowell
grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin hit his 11th home run to give Cincinnati a 1-0 lead
in the first. Kotsay snapped a 1-for-17 slump with his 11th homer
in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati scored twice in the sixth to take a 3-1 lead. Larkin
walked and Alex Ochoa singled against Vic Darensbourg. Chris Stynes
greeted Braden Looper with an RBI single, and when center fielder
Wilson threw wildly to the infield, Ochoa came home from first with
an unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds overcame a mental mistake by catcher Jason LaRue in the
sixth. When Wilson struck out for the second out with Henry
Rodriguez on first, LaRue tossed the ball to the ground and headed
for the dugout, thinking the inning was over, and Rodriguez raced
to second.
</P>
<P>
   But center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. chased down Lowell's 400-foot
fly to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Former Reds slugger Tony Perez, inducted into the Hall of
Fame this year, was honored before the game. Perez is now a special
assistant to Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski. ... Marlins
LF Cliff Floyd, sidelined since July 29 with a knee injury, is
expected to rejoin the lineup next week. ... Florida RHP Alex
Fernandez, who underwent season-ending shoulder surgery July 20,
said he's recovering well and hopes to pitch again by next May. ...
The Marlins passed the one-million mark in home attendance. ... The
Reds have played in front of 31 sellout crowds, 28 on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 0041 </TRAILER>
