<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart-Frascatore Argue in Dugout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Toronto pitching coach Dave Stewart had
to be restrained in the Blue Jays dugout during an argument with
reliever John Frascatore on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was physically held back from going after Frascatore by
bench coach Lee Elia and catcher Alberto Castillo before the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras showed an angry Stewart exchanging words with someone
out of sight in the tunnel leading to the Toronto dugout. After the
game Stewart confirmed he was yelling at Frascatore.
</P>
<P>
   ''John can never have my information again,'' Stewart said.
''John knows it all. Let him figure it out. From now on John
Frascatore is a pitching coach for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said the argument was over pitch selection in the
seventh inning. Frascatore came in to face pinch hitter Chad
Curtis, and he walked Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made a trip to the mound, and Frascatore got the next
batter, Luis Alicea, to ground out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a pitcher for 16 years and I never had a run-in with
anyone,'' Stewart said. ''This is a first. I'm embarrassed that it
took place in front of people in Toronto and sports viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   Frascatore refused to say what precipitated the argument.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was nothing,'' Frascatore said. ''Once you walk out of the
dugout, it's over. There's nothing there.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was something that happens in the heat of the moment. We're
in a pennant race. Stew and I are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto manager Jim Fregosi said the argument would not fester.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're both very much competitors,'' Fregosi said. ''In the
heat of battle they exchanged a few words. I talked to both of
them. It's over as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Frascatore is 1-3 with a 5.59 ERA in 50 appearances for the Blue
Jays this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
