<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
United, Pilots Reach Settlement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A tentative agreement was reached Saturday in a contract
dispute between United Airlines and its pilots which had forced the world's
largest airline to cancel or delay thousands of flights. The two sides met
around-the-clock over the past two days, guided by the National Mediation Board.
The key issues remaining in the talks were security and pay. A spokesman for the
pilots, Herb Hunter, would not provide any details of the agreement, which he
said is retroactive to April 12. The agreement will be presented to the pilots
next month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Joined Fires Gaining Western Ground
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Wildfires have burned together in southwestern
Montana's Bitterroot Valley and along the Continental Divide, forming the
nation's largest fire group, a federal official said Saturday. Elsewhere in the
West, South Dakota's governor urged residents of the central and southern Black
Hills to evacuate, and potential evacuation plans were ready for two small towns
threatened by a blaze in Washington. The Bitterroot Valley fire and the
Mussigbrod fires in the Big Hole River drainage covered an estimated 247,000
acres, said E. Lynn Burkett of the National Interagency Fire Center in Boise,
Idaho.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Praises Nigeria's President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) --President Clinton appealed to the leaders of this
oil-rich nation Saturday to set aside political acrimony so that their citizens
can lift themselves from poverty and isolation, calling Nigeria ''a pivot point
on which all Africa's future turns.'' Standing in the cavernous National
Assembly chamber Clinton praised President Olusegun Obasanjo's leadership in
stabilizing Nigeria. One of Clinton's purposes in coming was to encourage a
tender democracy to take root here in Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nader Hails WTO Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Green Party presidential hopeful Ralph Nader said Saturday
that last fall's World Trade Organization protests were a watershed in American
history, and he hopes the same populist wave responsible carries him to the
White House. Nader was still exulting from the biggest event of his campaign. On
Friday night, 10,000 people paid $7 each to hear him at the Memorial Coliseum in
Portland, Ore. He said Democratic nominee Vice President Al Gore and Republican
nominee George W. Bush could not have drawn that many people without help from
big-money contributors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woman Missing From Plane Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HILO, Hawaii (AP) -- A search continued Saturday for a woman missing from the
crash of a small sightseeing plane off the coast of Hawaii Island. The eight
people who survived Friday's crash were released from Hilo Medical Center on
Saturday, nursing supervisor Steve Palmore said. The missing woman was
identified by police as Laveta Rose Reynolds, 61, of North Collinsville, Okla.
Her 64-year-old husband, James Reynolds, was among the survivors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Releases U.S. Poet
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Boston poet detained in China for more than two weeks
arrived in the United States on Saturday, grateful for the outpouring of
international support for his case and concerned that family and friends could
be targeted by Chinese police. Police released Bei Lang, the editor of a
dissident literary journal, on Saturday, and sent him back to the United States,
removing an irritant in shaky but improving China-U.S. ties. Speaking by mobile
phone on the way to Beijing's airport, Bei said Chinese and U.S. diplomats
arranged his release to smooth the way for President Jiang Zemin's trip to New
York next month for a U.N. summit and talks with President Clinton.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wallace Wins Goracing.com 500
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) -- Rusty Wallace became the first four-time winner of the
season Saturday night when he easily won the goracing.com 500. The victory gave
him a season-sweep on the 0.533-mile bullring -- the first driver to pull off
the feat since Dale Earnhardt did it in 1987 -- and his ninth career win on the
concrete. Wallace, also the winner last week at Michigan, is the first driver
this season to win in consecutive weeks. More importantly, though, the Ford
driver closed the gap in the race for the Winston Cup championship. Wallace came
into the race in fifth place in the standings, 352 points behind leader Bobby
Labonte. Wallace remained in fifth after the win, but closed the gap to 290
points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mariners Beat White Sox 11-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The Mariners finally found some offensive pop again as Alex
Rodriguez homered and Mike Cameron had three RBIs to help Seattle win for just
the second time in 12 games, 11-5 over the Chicago White Sox on Saturday night.
John Halama (11-6), pitching for the first time in 10 days, gave up a single to
Frank Thomas with two out in the first inning and then retired 16 straight
batters before Tony Graffanino opened the seventh with a single.
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD 
</P>
