<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean President Appoints Advisor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- President Kim Dae-jung appointed a
career diplomat as his new national security adviser Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ha-joong, 53, chief presidential protocol secretary since
1998, succeeded Hwang Won-tak as the president's national security
adviser. Hwang, a retired army general, served in the post for one
year.
</P>
<P>
   The new national security adviser began his government career in
the foreign ministry in 1973. Before joining the presidential staff
in 1998, he had served as a diplomat in the United States, India,
Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
   Two other presidential staffers in charge of educational,
cultural, labor and welfare affairs were also replaced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The reshuffle of the presidential staff followed a major
reorganization of the government three weeks ago, in which eight of
the 18 Cabinet members were replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said the shake-up was part of the
president's effort to accelerate reform. A recent series of public
polls show people feel the Kim government is behind schedule in
economic and other reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
