<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Plane Crashes in Costa Rica  </HEADLINE>
By MARIANELA JIMENEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- A small airplane with 10 people on
board, including eight foreign tourists, crashed near a volcano in
a mountainous area of Costa Rica on Saturday. It was not known if
there were any survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-seat Caravan plane, operated by the company National
Aerial Services, was flying between the northern region of La
Fortuna, where the Arenal volcano is located, and Tamarindo, a
beach town on the Pacific coast, when it crashed, said Costa Rican
Interior Minister Rogelio Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   The plane took off from the capital, San Jose, at 12:15 p.m.,
stopping briefly in La Fortuna, where a Japanese passenger
deplaned, officials said. Air traffic controllers lost contact with
the plane at 1:30 p.m. and alerted rescue authorities, who had not
yet reached the scene early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos said at least 200 additional rescue workers would head for
the area at dawn Sunday. He said the plane had been spotted, but it
was not known if there were survivors.
</P>
<P>
   On board the airplane were the pilot and co-pilot, both from
Costa Rica, and eight foreigners, including two women who local
police and the Red Cross said were from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Residents heard an explosion at the time of the crash and saw
flames coming from the Chato hills, in the vicinity of the volcano,
local police official Walter Navarro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
