<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Missing From Plane Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILO, Hawaii (AP) -- A search on Saturday failed to locate a
woman missing from the crash of a small sightseeing plane off the
coast of Hawaii Island.
</P>
<P>
   The eight people who survived Friday's crash were released from
Hilo Medical Center on Saturday, nursing supervisor Steve Palmore
said.
</P>
<P>
   The missing woman was identified by police as Laveta Rose
Reynolds, 61, of North Collinsville, Okla. Her 64-year-old husband,
James Reynolds, was among the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's search effort was hampered by murky ocean conditions
and overcast skies, Assistant Fire Chief Crist Pung said. The
search was expected to resume Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter and rescue boat were used to rescue the survivors.
The 10-seat Piper Navajo Chieftain owned by tour and charter
company Big Island Air ditched in the ocean 200 yards from Honoli'i
Point, about four miles from Hilo International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigator Robert Crispin
said the pilot was headed for the airport after shutting down his
right engine, which had caught on fire. But with only one engine
running, the plane didn't have enough power to make it to the
airport, so the pilot had to set it down in the water, Crispin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Nicholas A. Vanus had reported engine problems, saying he
was going to ditch the plane, said Tom Hada, a Hawaiian Airlines
pilot who was waiting for takeoff from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knew he was going down,'' Hada said. ''This guy was real
calm. He had it together. He was definitely in control of the
situation, and he did a terrific job.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication Mrs. Reynolds got out of the plane
before it sank in more than 100 feet of water, Crispin said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reynolds couldn't swim, her daughter, Anissa Reynolds, told
Honolulu television station KHNL.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's always been deathly afraid of the water,'' Anissa
Reynolds said. ''She doesn't even like to go on a boat. She's
terrified of the water, so she can't swim.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Island Air owner Tom Beard said the flight originated from
Keahole-Kona International Airport, on the other side of the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Big Island Air: http://www.ilhawaii.net/pt/bigair.html
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board:
http://www.ntsb.gov/aviation/aviation.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
