<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unless more rainy weather comes, allergy sufferers can expect fall misery </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - After a rainy, cool summer, hay fever
sufferers in New Jersey could be especially miserable this fall,
unless Mother Nature cuts them a break - by dumping even more rain
here over the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Above-average rainfall, particularly this month, combined with
record-cool weather last month, have helped ragweed and other such
pollen-producers to thrive. At the same time, the limited number of
sunny days in the ''heat of summer'' kept ragweed, outdoor molds
and other allergy triggers from drying out and burning up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything's growing like crazy,'' said Dr. Catherine
Monteleone, an allergist/immunologist and associate professor of
medicine at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey
in New Brunswick. ''Now if we start getting dry, windy days in the
fall, all that pollen is primed to be released.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragweed, in particular, produces large amounts of pollen that is
very light and can be carried for miles through the air. A leafy
green plant with a yellow crown that can reach several feet tall,
it grows wild in fields, yards and even sidewalk cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Monteleone said the best hope for the roughly 10 percent of
people with seasonal hay fever is just what everyone's been
complaining about: rainy weather.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rain washes the pollen out of the air, so if we get lots of
rain, people will suffer less,'' Monteleone said.
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure what kind of weather the late summer and
early fall will bring, but there's no question the state hasn't had
much of a summer so far.
</P>
<P>
   New Brunswick tied the record for the coolest July in the 108
years records have been kept, with an average temperature of 71.4
degrees - more than three degrees below the norm, according to
assistant state climatologist Keith Arnesen.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the average temperature in July was even lower, 70.8
degrees, also more than three degrees below the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a very unusual combination of spring and summer,''
Arnesen said, with March through June posting warmer-than-usual
average temperatures statewide.
</P>
<P>
   After the cool July weather, the average temperature in New
Brunswick so far in August is about 1.5 degrees below normal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, precipitation has been well above normal since June.
The statewide average rainfall that month, 4.32 inches, was
two-thirds of an inch above normal, while July's 5.34-inch
statewide average was almost an inch above normal. Through early
last week, New Brunswick had received 6.21 inches of rain in
August, nearly 50 percent more than the norm for the entire month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite similar weather throughout much of the Northeast,
Arnesen noted that for the entire United States this January
through July ''turns out to be the warmest first seven months of
any year on record.''
</P>
<P>
   If September turns out to be warm and dry here, Monteleone says
allergy sufferers can take several steps to reduce their exposure
to ragweed:
</P>
<P>
   -At home and in the car, keep windows shut and air conditioning
on. That can decrease the amount of pollen coming into a home
ten-thousandfold.
</P>
<P>
   -Avoid doing yardwork or exercising outside until early evening,
when pollen levels fall. Consider wearing a face mask while
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   -Wipe down pets' fur with a damp cloth when they come indoors.
</P>
<P>
   -Shower before going to sleep to prevent bringing pollen into
the bed.
</P>
<P>
   For people who know their allergies generally are bad in the
fall, Monteleone said the best thing is to see a doctor as soon as
possible to try one of many relatively new medications on the
market. They include eyedrops, nasal sprays and allergy pills that
don't have the unpleasant side effects, particularly drowsiness,
that earlier pills did.
</P>
<P>
   Monteleone noted that medications have improved so much that
many allergists have seen the portion of their practice devoted to
giving allergy shots drop from 50 percent to about 10 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
