<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman complies with ethics rules but law says she doesn't have to </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman returns to the
Statehouse Monday after a California trip spent mountain biking
near San Francisco and politicking in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For her time off, Whitman took vacation days, just like any
other state employee.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike any other worker on the public payroll, the governor
didn't need to use personal time for her days spent as the
Republican Party cheerleader outside the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The law that mandates personal time for personal business
applies to only state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is not hired to do a job - she's elected. In the state's
conflict of interest law, that's a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Every governor since the law was created in 1972 has complied,
but they do so saying the measure does not specifically apply to
the chief executive, said Rita L. Strmensky, director of the
state's Executive Commission on Ethical Standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been arguments made that the governor is not
subject to the law because the governor is the only elected
official in the executive branch, all others are employees,''
Strmensky said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no special rule that applies to the governor,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the ethics law says personal business should be done
on personal time. State employees who engage in political
activities - fund raising, campaigning, public speaking - during
normal work hours, must use vacation days or take a leave of
absence
</P>
<P>
   The administrative ethics code for the governor's office says
that rule applies to all employees and mirrors the language in the
state law, Strmensky said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, no mention is made for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is simply not clear if the Legislature intended to govern
the conduct of the governor by the ethics law. There is a valid
legal question here,'' Strmensky said.
</P>
<P>
   As New Jersey's first woman governor, Whitman became a popular
Republican standard-bearer, buoyed in part by the national
reputation that followed her early income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   By one count, Whitman has visited more than 25 states
campaigning for state and national Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, she has fastidiously maintained a self-imposed
wall between public and partisan travel, Whitman spokesman Pete
McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She always takes that time as vacation time and doesn't have a
large entourage with her,'' McDonough said. Her expenses outside
the state are always covered by a candidate or political party in
those cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not proper to be campaigning at the taxpayer's expense,''
he said. ''Any elected official that did is foolish. It's silly.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's visit to Los Angeles to offer the Republican spin on
the Democratic convention was no exception, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee paid her expenses, and
Whitman's office submitted a vacation request. As governor, Whitman
is eligible for 20 vacation days, three personal days as well as
paid sick time.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough, the only staff member to accompany her, said he took
vacation time as well.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republican convention in Philadelphia, Whitman followed
her same rule, but again enjoyed one notable exception allowed by
state law.
</P>
<P>
   All the time she spent hosting the Republican delegates in their
New Jersey hotel, Whitman was not a partisan politician, but
technically still the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Cherry Hill, she's still the governor. She's not the
governor when she's out of state,'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and some of her paid staff members did take personal
time for their days at the Republican convention, but only those
who were there for purely political reasons, McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Many staff members accompanied Whitman to the convention hotel
were doing their state jobs, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The scheduler still needs to make the governor's schedule.
That's clearly government work,'' McDonough said. ''She is still
the governor, and it has to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
