<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over a quiet beach, a loud debate about access  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A compromise plan for access to one of New
Jersey's most protected beaches has managed to anger both
conservationists and fishermen, who had been on opposite sides of
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service wants to limit access by
beach buggies to Holgate Beach, a 3-mile piece of federally
protected wilderness at the southern tip of Long Beach Island.
</P>
<P>
   Motorized vehicles would be banned from land above mean high
tide, which is owned by the federal government, but not from land
below mean high tide, which is owned by New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmental groups are angry that the Fish and Wildlife
Service gave up its original proposal to ask the state to join in
the ban, a step that would have exiled motorized vehicles from
Holgate Beach altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilderness Society, a conservation group, urged the
government to stick by its initial proposal. The group complained
that ''motorized trespassers'' are spreading garbage and disturbing
several federally protected species, including the piping plover, a
small bird.
</P>
<P>
   ''No longer is Holgate a place where visitors can find solitude
and remoteness that wilderness is supposed to provide,'' the group
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But some fishing groups say even the revised Fish and Wildlife
proposal is unnecessary and could, depending on tides, stop
fishermen from driving their equipment to favorite fishing spots.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all the heavy tackle and coolers - and presumably you're
going to carry a big fish back too - it's a long, tough walk,''
said Bob DeLeonard, president of the New Jersey Beach Buggy
Association, which represents surf fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the government designated as wilderness more than 6,600
acres of the Edwin B. Forsythe National Wildlife Refuge - including
the 3-mile stretch of Holgate Beach. A prior law, the 1964
Wilderness Act, barred use of motor vehicles in wilderness areas.
The Fish and Wildlife Service says beach buggies have therefore
been illegal on Holgate Beach for 25 years, although a ban was
never enforced.
</P>
<P>
   A 1989 compromise between the government and fishermen keeps
vehicles out of the Holgate area from April 15 to Sept. 1 every
year, during breeding season of the piping plover. But fishermen
still can drive onto the beach in the fall, their prime season.
</P>
<P>
   A new battle began in 1997, when Congress directed the Interior
Department to prepare 15-year plans for each of the nation's 514
national wildlife refuges.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for the Forsythe refuge called for adding 16,900 acres
to its current size of 43,656 acres, creating new trails, fishing
piers, hunting areas and visitors centers - and closing the Holgate
wilderness area to motorized vehicles year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the Fish and Wildlife Service would close
federal land near beach dunes to motor vehicles and seek a license
from the New Jersey Tidelands Council to close state-owned land
closer to the surf.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service held public meetings in Cape May,
Atlantic and Ocean counties and received more than 1,600 letters,
many objecting to the proposed ban on motor vehicles on Holgate
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the service issued its scaled-back proposal that has
satisfied neither side in the debate: Holgate Beach above mean high
tide would be closed year-round to motor vehicles, but no effort
would be made to ban vehicles on state land below mean high tide.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the refuge manager would try to introduce ferry service to
carry fishermen and others from populated Long Beach Island to the
southern tip of the Holgate Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision is due by the Fish and Wildlife Service next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge is named for a former congressman, Edwin B. Forsythe,
described by DeLeonard as ''an avid beach buggy surf fisherman.''
DeLeonard said Forsythe, who served from 1970 until his death in
1984, would be ''shocked and dismayed'' that beach buggy access to
Holgate Beach is now threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Saxton, R-Mount Holly, succeeded Forsythe in Congress
and has sided with fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is unreasonable to impose this kind of restriction on a
historic, beneficial use of public lands,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
