<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fears Rise on Lebanon Frontier  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FATIMA GATE, Lebanon (AP) -- As the Israeli patrol jeep
approached, kicking up white dust, Mohammed Khalil swung into
action. The 24-year-old man grabbed a rock the size of a football
and hurled it over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an enemy that occupied our land and expelled us from
our homes,'' said the bearded Shiite Muslim, a coffee vendor,
dusting off his hands. ''That's the least we could do.''
</P>
<P>
   This time the rock bounced harmlessly off the bulletproof
windshield and the jeep sped on. But things don't always end so
peacefully, and the daily stonings, fire-bombings and verbal taunts
are turning the Fatima Gate into a flash point.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has reported more than 370 incidents to the United
Nations since it withdrew in May, ending 24 years of military
involvement in Lebanon. By Lebanese and Israeli count, eight
Israeli soldiers and a dozen Arabs have been injured. Israel says
it has had enough and insists the Lebanese authorities keep the
peace. Lebanon says it won't act as Israel's policeman.
</P>
<P>
   The fear on both sides is that an incident could get out of hand
and draw Israeli troops and Hezbollah guerrillas into a renewal of
the fighting that raged for 18 years until the Israelis left.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has sent peacekeeping troops into the former
Israeli zone but has steered away from the former crossing point at
Fatima Gate. It too has hinted that the Lebanese should take
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.N. is not responsible for guarding the border,'' said
Timur Goksel, adviser to the commander of the 5,000-member U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''Border monitoring is our function. Border security is
essentially a national responsibility,'' Goksel said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government has sent 1,000 soldiers and policemen
south but is staying away from Fatima Gate, confining itself
largely to two bases in towns near the border.
</P>
<P>
   So Hezbollah guerrillas remain in charge at the Fatima Gate,
where some Lebanese homes are just a few paces from the fence and
the red roofs of the Israeli village of Metulla are an apple grove
away.
</P>
<P>
   Unarmed guerrillas wearing civilian clothes walk back and forth
along the former crossing point, recognizable only by their two-way
radios.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere along the border, the guerrillas are quick to turn
people away from the fence, but here, stone-throwers are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is happening is just a symbolic expression before the
cameras,'' Hezbollah leader Sheik Hassan Nasrallah said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The spot is weighted with symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers say the gate was named for a peasant girl whose
wounded mother cried out for her after the two were caught in a gun
battle along the fence between Israeli troops and Palestinian
guerrillas in 1976. The woman was taken to Israel for treatment and
the next day an Israeli soldier called out to Fatima that her
mother was fine.
</P>
<P>
   It also became known as the Good Fence, where Lebanese living in
the occupied border zone used to cross into Israel for jobs and
medical care, and where last May some 6,000 former Israeli-allied
militiamen and their families fled into exile in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Today, parents bring their children to walk and take pictures.
Scouts and school children come by the busload.
</P>
<P>
   Stonings ebb and flow depending on the crowd size and mood.
Weekends are generally busier.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious incident, Israeli soldiers opened fire June
24 when two men tried to climb over the fence. Three Jordanian
trade unionists, part of a delegation shouting insults at the
Israelis, were injured along with one Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, a crowd was preparing to throw a firebomb when
soldiers opened fire, injuring a Canadian and a Lebanese journalist
and a Lebanese teen-ager who was throwing stones.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes stones hit soldiers, injuring them. Sometimes the
soldiers throw stones back.
</P>
<P>
   A local contractor has donated piles of stones and gravel, which
are regularly replenished.
</P>
<P>
   Many visitors just come to gaze into Israel. And on the other
side, Lebanese exiles come to stare at their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The 700-yard (637-meter) strip on the Lebanese side has become a
promenade. Stalls sell juice, coffee, tea, biscuits and corn on the
cob. Three Hezbollah stalls play tapes of guerrilla anthems and
speeches, and sell Hezbollah flags, baseball caps, tapes and
posters.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Said, the Palestinian-American writer, tossed a stone
here last month. He explained later: ''The spirit of the place
infected everyone with the same impulse, to make a symbolic gesture
of joy that the occupation had ended.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
