<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. May Be Key To House Control  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORRISTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- A first-term congressman in a fickle
district, Democratic Rep. Joe Hoeffel was explaining his vote
against cutting taxes on Social Security benefits when the fax
machine spit out a Republican attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's wrong to punish seniors with a tax on those hard-earned
benefits,'' read the GOP charge.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Hoeffel told reporters questioning him in the
basement of the county courthouse that Republicans were ''pandering
to seniors'' with a tax cut. The legislation, he said, shortchanged
Medicare by taking away a guaranteed source of its funding.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel's ability to persuade voters with his argument in one of
the nation's classic swing districts will go a long way toward
determining whether he can defeat his moderate Republican rival,
state Sen. Stewart Greenleaf.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a personal battle, strategists in both parties agree
the race is one of about 30 most likely to determine whether
Democrats or Republicans win control of the House on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   From the well-manicured lawns on Philadelphia's Main Line to the
grittier precincts around Norristown, Pennsylvania's 13th
Congressional District is so politically competitive it has sent
four different representatives to Congress in the last five
elections.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, Lawrence Coughlin, held the seat for nearly a
quarter century before retiring in 1992. His departure set off a
series of close elections in the changing district, often in rough
harmony with national trends.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky, won the seat in 1992,
the year Bill Clinton was elected president. But she unexpectedly
voted for a tax increase as part of Clinton's budget package --
including the tax on some Social Security benefits that Hoeffel
recently voted not to repeal -- and lost the seat in the GOP
landslide of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, Jon Fox, held sway for two terms before losing to
Hoeffel in 1998, when Democrats unexpectedly won seats nationwide
but fell short of regaining control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   This time, predicts Mark Gersh, a strategist and longtime
adviser to House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt, ''neither side is
going to win by more than a few (percentage) points.''
</P>
<P>
   The district is Republican by registration, moderate by
ideology, better educated than the nation as a whole, according to
strategists on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a race closely watched by both parties, the candidates
are getting high-profile help. Speaker Dennis Hastert and Majority
Leader Dick Armey both have campaigned for Greenleaf. Sen. John
McCain, who showed strong support from independents during the
presidential primaries, also stopped in the district on his way to
the Republicans' convention this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel joined Clinton at a fund-raiser in Philadelphia earlier
in the year, netting more than $100,000 for his campaign. He's also
been visited by Gephardt and Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., leader
of the party's campaign money operation in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Soft spoken, Greenleaf has a self-deprecating side. He said that
anyone who blinked would have missed his brief appearance at the
GOP convention podium.
</P>
<P>
   To the relief of party officials in Washington, he won a primary
over a conservative challenger, and other Republicans point to
polls showing Hoeffel under 50 percent in support, a traditional
sign of danger for an incumbent. At the same time, GOP strategists
fret privately that Hoeffel had more than $800,000 in the bank as
of June 30, compared to slightly more than $400,000 for Greenleaf.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to separate himself from the party's conservatives in
Congress, Greenleaf described himself as a ''social moderate'' on
women's and children's issues and the environment and said he will
not ''rubber stamp'' anything.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said he will stress three issues this fall:
Social Security and Medicare, education, and cutting taxes while
paying attention to the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would pay off the debt,'' Greenleaf said. But at the same
time when opportunity arises for tax cuts ''you have to jump at it.
You have to grab any middle class tax reduction'' that's available.
He supported recent GOP legislation to reduce the so-called
marriage penalty, adding that 62,000 taxpayers in his district
would have benefited had Clinton not vetoed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel voted against the GOP marriage penalty bill, well aware
that voting for a tax increase -- rather than a tax cut -- did in
Margolies-Mezvinsky, the last Democrat to hold the seat.
</P>
<P>
   But circumstances are different now, he said, ''She said up to
the day of the vote she would vote no,'' then cast her vote in
favor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That last-minute switch, he added, ''allowed the Republicans to
call her a liar, and that's what many did, for 15 months.''
</P>
<P>
   In his case, he noted he's voted consistently against GOP tax
cut proposals and in favor of more modest Democratic alternatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
