<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribute for UK Trapped Airmen  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD MIDDLETON
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) -- With the laying of wreaths and a
Scottish piper's lament, Britain's Royal Air Force paid tribute
Sunday to four World War II airmen whose bodies were trapped inside
an Icelandic glacier for nearly 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The men's remains were retrieved last week during a three-day
expedition to the wreckage of their Fairey Battle bomber plane,
which crashed in May 1941.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the four were accorded full military honors at a
commemorative service at Reykjavik's Fossfogur cemetery attended by
their relatives, RAF officials and dignitaries from several
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today is bringing an issue to a final close. It now means that
we have been given a final resting place,'' said Arthur Fickling,
the namesake nephew of the plane's pilot, Arthur Round of
Wellington, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most poignant offerings was a bouquet of six red roses
sent from New Zealand by Round's childhood sweetheart, 83-year-old
Nan Poole. ''Thanks for many happy memories, dear 'Arsa,' your old
pal Nan,'' the card read.
</P>
<P>
   The airmen's plane crashed in thick fog shortly after takeoff
from Akureyri airport in north Iceland. The site near the glacial
summit of a 4,000-foot mountain was located two days later and a
short funeral service was held, but the spot was quickly lost in a
blanket of snow and ice.
</P>
<P>
   It was rediscovered last year by Icelandic historian Ordur
Geirsson after a 20-year search, inspired by tales of Round's
aviation skills.
</P>
<P>
   During a 15-minute service at a simple Lutheran church, prayers
were said Sunday for Round, who died two days after his 19th
birthday, and his three English colleagues -- radio operator
Reginald Hopkins, 21, of Southampton, Flight Sgt. Keith Garrett,
22, of Worksop, and Pilot Officer Henry Talbot, 24, of North
Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the central altar were a raised candle ringed by red
carnations and four other candles, representing the dead airmen.
</P>
<P>
   After the service, the 150-strong congregation walked the short
way to the communal grave site, where the headstones have been
engraved with the RAF's motto in Latin, translating to ''through
difficulties to the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   As a piper began to play ''Flowers of the Forest,'' a lament
dating from the Battle of Flodden in 1513, a RAF Nimrod flew
overhead, followed in its tribute by an Icelandic coast guard
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   As the noise of the aircraft died away in the still, overcast
morning, 10 relatives stepped forward to lay their own personal
wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''We always felt that there was much more to my uncle's death
than my family were told at the time,'' said Keith Slaney of
Costhorp, England, named after his uncle, airman Keith Garrett.
''Now that we have had this service to go to, it closes the final
chapter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1314 </TRAILER>
