<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Reps Don't Fly Stage Flag  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Often lost among the four flags standing
outside Rep. Cynthia McKinney's Washington office is the one that's
missing.
</P>
<P>
   In McKinney's doorway, you can find banners of the American
Stars and Stripes, the Olympic games, DeKalb County, Ga., and one
commemorating prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   But the official flag of Georgia -- the one that includes a large
Confederate X -- is nowhere to be found, even though state flags are
customary office decor for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney and fellow Georgia Democrat John Lewis, a former civil
rights leader, choose not to display the flag because they find it
divisive. Yet it's a quiet protest -- one that was never really
announced.
</P>
<P>
   If asked, they'll share their opinions that the banner should be
redrawn, that the current version was adopted in 1956 as an act of
racist defiance against school desegregation rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be laid to rest,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes down to it, Lewis and McKinney know the matter
is out of their hands. They're reluctant to carry the cause much
further and are perfectly willing to leave it up to the Democratic
governor and Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of now, I don't plan to get up there and fight,'' Lewis
said. ''I'll fight on an individual level for myself, and the day
may come when it may be needed for me to play a much more involved
role. But there's very little we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some critics of the state flag contend that now is
the perfect time to take aim. After all, it's an election year, and
the Confederate banner over South Carolina's Capitol created quite
a stir when George W. Bush and John McCain went to that state in
pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only Georgia and Mississippi feature the Confederate emblem
on their official flags -- and it's much larger on Georgia's.
</P>
<P>
   The other 11 members of the state's Congressional delegation
display the flag, including Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop, who
like McKinney and Lewis is black. Bishop declined to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The flag was also one of the first pieces of decoration that
arrived at the Washington office of Democrat Zell Miller, appointed
last month to fill the Senate vacancy left by the death of
Republican Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a former two-term governor, almost lost his re-election
bid after leading an unsuccessful crusade in 1993 to change the
flag. Now he faces another campaign in November against former Sen.
Mack Mattingly for the right to finish the four years left on
Coverdell's term.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by Georgia State University earlier this year indicates
the flag issue could be political poison. In that poll, 56 percent
wanted to keep it the way it was, and only 31 percent wanted to
change it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might be the right thing to do. But if there's not a lot of
public support behind you, it's the sort of thing politicians would
like to avoid,'' Michael Binford, a Georgia State political
scientist, said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans figure Georgia's Democrats are trying to have
it both ways. They argue they're trying to use the flag as a tool
to attack GOP supporters yet avoid messing with it, fearing the
wrath of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they're serious about it, they should come up with a
formula,'' said Rep. Jack Kingston, a Republican who says he would
like the Legislature to call meetings to discuss the matter. ''The
lack of leadership is astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingston said he suspects Democrats might be forming a
''backroom plan'' to wait until after the November elections and
then call a statewide referendum for 2002, when Gov. Roy Barnes
leaves office and a successor is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would bring out the vote and help their side,'' Kingston
said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the South Carolina primary was any indication, the matter
could be hashed out before then -- especially if Georgia lives up to
its billing as a ''battleground state.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee for president,
has already criticized Bush's position not to meddle in South
Carolina's affairs. Such a fight could be headed to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   There have already been some previews.
</P>
<P>
   In March, students at Centennial High School in Fulton County
voted against flying the state flag at the building. And earlier
this month, the NCAA Executive Committee turned down calls by civil
rights group to move three upcoming Final Four basketball
tournaments out of Atlanta because of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Georgia flag was at the center of a spat between
lawmakers in Georgia and New York. Gov. George Pataki approved its
removal from the New York Capitol, and two Georgia lawmakers
retaliated by taking down New York's flag from their Capitol
rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pranksters, Georgia Senate Minority Leader Eric
Johnson, said he expects the issue will emerge again soon -- and
once again, he'll oppose any change.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pickup trucks, deer hunting, barefoot girls and boiled peanuts
-- that's what the flag represents to the vast majority of
Georgians,'' Johnson said. ''Nobody looks at it as a symbol of
hate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000827.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Crunch Hits Numbers Crunchers  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government's numbers crunchers quietly
churn out data vital to tracking the economy's pulse and making
informed policy and business decisions. But they may have to pare
back if Congress doesn't come up with more money soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have reached the point where -- it's not the rubber hitting
the road. It's the rim hitting the road,'' said Robert Shapiro, the
Commerce Department's under secretary for economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bureau of Economic Analysis, one of the department's main
numbers-crunching units, the budget has declined in real, inflation
adjusted terms by 12 percent over the last five years, agency
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the BEA produces the Holy Grail of economic
statistics: the Gross Domestic Product, the total output of goods
and services within the United States. It's just one of the reports
the Federal Reserve looks at when making interest rate policies --
decisions that affect millions of consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   BEA's current budget is $43.8 million. The House voted to
provide another $43.8 million to BEA in fiscal year 2001, which
begins Oct. 1, an amount that Shapiro said would cause cutbacks to
the agency's economic data. The Senate Appropriations Committee,
meanwhile, has proposed $48.3 million -- close to the nearly $49
million President Clinton requested.
</P>
<P>
   BEA's funding issue probably won't be resolved until sometime
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can no longer guarantee the timeliness and frequency of
these economic measures if Congress were to go ahead and cut BEA
again in real terms as the House mark would do,'' Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   If BEA doesn't get more money this year, Shapiro said the agency
is considering a number of possibilities including: producing two
estimates of GDP per quarter instead of the current three; doing
the trade report quarterly rather than monthly; and producing state
personal income reports annually instead of quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce also is looking to get more money for numbers crunchers
at its Census Bureau, whose economic data includes reports tracking
housing, construction and retail activity. It also teams up with
the BEA for the monthly trade report.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is small change -- in a huge budget of over $1.7 trillion
-- to produce the basic data that the economy runs on,'' Shapiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a leading group of economists, the National
Association for Business Economics, said topping their list of
concerns is adequate funding for the government's numbers
crunchers.
</P>
<P>
   ''These data are critical to maintaining the prosperity that we
have enjoyed,'' said Diane Swonk, president of NABE and chief
economist for Bank One Corp. ''They shape business policy and
provide the very core of policy-making decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: BEA's web site: http://www.bea.doc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1321 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000827.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Vote in Marrred Elections  </HEADLINE>
By RODEINA KENAAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAABDAT, Lebanon (AP) -- With security forces guarding towns and
polling stations in central and northern Lebanon, Lebanese voted
for parliamentary representatives Sunday in an election sure to
pack the legislature with pro-Syrian representatives.
</P>
<P>
   As is typical of elections held since the end of the 1975-1990
civil war, there were limited complaints about irregularities,
including the presence of uncertified ballots, the absence of names
on voters' lists, forged voter registration cards and the lack of
secrecy in casting ballots leaving voters open to intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the complaints, the polling was peaceful and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   The capital Beirut and the eastern and southern provinces will
vote next Sunday. It will be the first time in nearly three decades
that southern regions near the border with Israel will vote, an
event made possible by the Israeli withdrawal from a border buffer
zone in May.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's voting, some 286 candidates -- most of whom had
Syria's tacit approval -- contested 63 seats in the 128-member
legislature for the provinces of Mount Lebanon and North Lebanon,
the Christian heartland where 1.3 million Lebanese over the age of
21 were eligible to vote. Polling stations in Mount Lebanon's four
electoral districts and the North's three districts opened at 7
a.m. and closed at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Christian groups had called for a boycott of the
elections to protest what they described as Syria's packaging of
the ballot to ensure a loyal parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But their call went largely unheeded, and the voting is expected
to ensure a four-year parliament packed with pro-Syrians. Syria is
the main power in Lebanon with 30,000 troops deployed across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Initial results were expected as early as Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 soldiers on Sunday manned checkpoints and major
road intersections or patrolled in armored vehicles to ensure
violence-free balloting. Police were in charge inside polling
stations. Weapons licenses were canceled and about 120 people have
been arrested for violating the ban. All nightclubs and restaurants
in Mount Lebanon and the North have been ordered closed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Armenian quarter of Bourj Hammoud, opponents mobbed the
car of an Armenian candidate on a list headed by legislator Nassib
Lahoud, a former ambassador to Washington battling against Interior
Minister Michel Murr.
</P>
<P>
   President Emile Lahoud was among the morning voters, casting his
ballot at a polling station in the post office at his Mount Lebanon
hometown of Baabdat, 10 miles northeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am proud,'' a beaming Lahoud told reporters later. ''This is
the first time I've voted in my life,'' said Lahoud, a 64-year-old
former army commander who could not vote in the past because of
military regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Lahoud called on voters not to be swayed by the influence of
money. ''He who buys you can sell you. ... Vote your conscience,''
said Lahoud, a Maronite Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I voted for the good people,'' George Massoud, a 70-year-old
grocer said as he opened his store for business after casting his
ballot in Baabdat.
</P>
<P>
   Druse leader Walid Jumblatt charged that the government was
heavily involved on the side of his challengers. ''They are
hysterical. They lost their nerve,'' he said of the campaign
against him in the Chouf district.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Editor's Note: Associated Press Writer Joseph Panossian
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1334 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
