<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian sailors honored at U.S. Naval Submarine Base  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GROTON, Conn. (AP) - The 118 sailors who perished two weeks ago
aboard the Russian nuclear submarine Kursk were honored Saturday
during a ceremony at the U.S. Naval Submarine Base.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people attended, including former submariners, sailors
and their families.
</P>
<P>
   John Carcioppolo, commander of the Groton Navy base and a former
Chief of the Boat on the U.S.S. Dallas, and other members of the
Submarine Veterans Inc., of Groton and the Submarine Veterans of
World War II organized the mid-morning service along the Thames
River.
</P>
<P>
   Taps was played as the crowd stood near the USS Nautilus
Memorial, and a bell was struck 118 times to pay homage to the
Russian sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we drop the political differences of the two countries
that were almost enough to escalate to the point of war,''
Carcioppolo said. ''We are here to honor and pay our respects to
other submariners that are now on eternal patrol.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kimo Ward of Montville, the memorial service was an
opportunity to pay tribute to all submariners who have perished at
sea, including former friends as well as adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping a wreath in the river, Ward said the fate of the Kursk
brought back painful memories of friends who died aboard the
Thresher, which sank more than 30 years ago, killing all on board.
The United States has lost two nuclear submarines at sea - the
Thresher in 1963 and the Scorpion in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, a retired sonar technician, was involved in the searches
for both, which took place in the days after the submarines
disappeared. Neither was ever found.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just another needless tragedy,'' Ward said of the
Kursk. ''But this is also something that you have to deal with
because we know it can happen at any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian nuclear sub sank in the Barents Sea two weeks ago
after two explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Russian experts have not conclusively determined what was
responsible for the blasts. Military officials say the most likely
scenario was that the Kursk collided with another vessel, most
likely a foreign submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Both Britain and the United States denied their submarines
collided with the Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the most likely reason for the sinking was an
internal malfunction and explosion in the submarine's torpedo
compartment. Russian officials also have not ruled out the
possibility that the Kursk hit a World War II-era mine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-27-00 1340 </TRAILER>
