<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Asks For Help  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Behind the throng of poor and unemployed
straining to catch a glimpse of President Clinton in his passing
motorcade, a white banner summed up the hopes of many Nigerians:
''This is the time to cancel Nigeria's debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled by staggering loan payments accumulated under brutal
dictators of the past, Nigeria has asked Clinton to help them fight
alarming poverty by canceling its share of the West African'
nation's estimated $32 billion in international debt.
</P>
<P>
   In an impassioned speech at a banquet held in Clinton's honor
Saturday night, President Olusegun Obasanjo, Nigeria's first
civilian leader in 15 years, blamed unpaid debts for entrenching
the divide between rich and poor in Nigeria and other impoverished
African states. The U.S. share of Nigeria's debt is estimated at
close to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''The transfer of wealth from the very poor to the very rich
must stop,'' Obasanjo said, calling debt cancellation a ''moral
responsibility and a humane duty.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent reward for Obasanjo's earlier pledge to work to
''bring an element of stability'' to skyrocketing world oil prices,
Clinton has said the United States will offer relief and debt
rescheduling if Nigeria fights corruption and uses its savings to
improve roads, health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   ''I agree that we should help you with the debt burden, as long
as you are going to spend the savings of the debt on the real human
and economic longterm needs of the people of Nigeria,'' he said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Since Obasanjo won elections in 1999 ending years of military
rule, U.S. aid to Nigeria has grown from almost nothing to about
$170 million a year -- making it the biggest U.S. aid recipient in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration has consistently rejected calls for
the sweeping debt cancellation that African governments argue they
need to overcome poverty, AIDS and a legacy of dictatorships and
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria says it will remain unable to rebuild the roads, clinics
and schools left to decay by a succession of military regimes.
</P>
<P>
   The government says debt payments soak up much of state oil
revenues, the world's sixth-largest. The civil service teeters on
collapse and Nigeria can afford to spend only $1 per person
annually on health compared, compared to the $60 minimum
recommended by the U.N. World Health Organization, Obasanjo said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and teachers go unpaid, universities are without books
and sometimes sell diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some foreign diplomats and Nigerians fear that debt relief
intended to help the poor could end up enriching crooked government
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo has made fighting corruption a priority, yet civil
servants still routinely demand bribes and Nigerian newspapers are
filled with allegations of government graft.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent 77-page letter to Clinton, Gani Fawehinmi, a
well-known opposition activist, asked the United States to forgive
past loans but warned them against granting any in the future,
saying there was nothing to prevent officials from stealing more.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you insist on advancing with such (future) loans, then you
must understand that you are on your own and that Nigerians cannot
accept any responsibility for them,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian Presidential Spokesman Doyin Okupe said Sunday his
government was pleased with the growing U.S. commitment to Nigeria,
which he hoped would overcome Clinton's refusal to cancel Nigerian
debt by providing spinoff economic benefits in oil, agriculture and
other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if the debt question is not fully addressed as most
people would have expected, there is now some light at the end of
the tunnel,'' Okupe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1352 </TRAILER>
