<HEADLINE> Journalist in Texas and New York dies of rare bone cancer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. (AP) - Karen Potter, who spent a decade
covering Texas politics for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram and later
worked as the managing editor/features at the Times Union in
Albany, died Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   She was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Potter died at her home after battling a rare form of bone
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Gov. Ann Richards said Potter, who was raised in
Oklahoma and trained in Texas, stood out from the statehouse press
corps in Austin as ''a little more gracious in her manner, a little
more thoughtful in her questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Karen was a plain solid citizen, one of the most balanced
people I ever met. She had such a cool hand,'' said Molly Ivins,
author, syndicated political columnist and a colleague of Potter's
at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Potter completed dual degrees in journalism and marketing at
Southern Methodist University in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fort Worth paper, she became the youngest state Capitol
bureau chief at 30 and won numerous journalism awards for her
investigative work.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the Times Union in 1995, Potter produced an
award-winning series on domestic violence, nurtured in-depth
projects on autism and hospice care, introduced long human-interest
narratives told in short chapters and encouraged a whimsical take
on celebrity, popular culture and fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   ''No editor was held in higher regard,'' said Jeff Cohen, Times
Union vice president and editor. ''She was kind and careful. One
reporter told me her side of the newsroom, the Features Department,
was Shangri-La.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter's husband, Steve Campbell, is a Times Union sports
columnist. Their daughter, Olivia Sarah, is 11 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Services will be held Tuesday at Jonesville United Methodist
Church.
</P>
</TEXT>
