<HEADLINE> Parks worker stabbed in Central Park  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A homeless man stabbed a Parks Department
maintenance worker who tried to move him out of a public bathroom
in Central Park Sunday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   William Gillum, 49, allegedly stabbed Terry Richards, 36, in the
forearm inside a public bathroom near the tennis courts at 93rd
Street on the west side of the park at 11:45 a.m., said police and
Parks Commissioner Henry Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Richards ''asked him to leave, he refused, he tried to remove
him and he was stabbed with a knife,'' Stern said. ''Despite his
injuries, he chased his assailant.''
</P>
<P>
   Police apprehended Gillum in the park's North Meadow at 97th
Street. He was charged with assault and criminal possession of a
weapon, said Officer Joseph Cavitolo, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, a temporary Parks employee, was in stable condition,
Cavitolo said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern emphasized that there was no danger to those who use
Central Park, but said his department and the police would step up
efforts to prevent homeless people from loitering there.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a park cleaner and he was doing his job when this
happened,'' Stern said. ''This is not a situation that any park
user is likely to get into.''
</P>
</TEXT>
