<HEADLINE> With BC-NY--America's Reckoning, Bjt  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - In the last four years, an estimated $9
billion has been pledged for a variety of funds to benefit victims
of Nazi persecution, according to the World Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sources of the money:
</P>
<P>
   - $5 billion from German government and industry to be paid
largely to former forced and slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   - $1.2 billion from Swiss banks to pay for dormant accounts
never returned to victims or heirs.
</P>
<P>
   - $700 million from France for pensions for Holocaust orphans
and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   - $500 million from insurance companies for claims never paid on
policyholders who died.
</P>
<P>
   - $400 million from Holland's government, banks, stock exchange
and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   - $200 million from the Swiss in a humanitarian fund for needy
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   - $60 million from looted gold, agreed to by more than a dozen
participating countries.
</P>
