<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> District attorneys vary widely in pressing for death penalty  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL ZEIGLER
Democrat and Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - For New York capital murder defendants,
where they committed their crimes can determine whether they live
or die.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of statistics since the law took effect Sept. 1,
1995, found that upstate prosecutors pursue the death penalty at
nearly four times the rate of their downstate counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Although nearly one-third of indictments for first-degree murder
are in Manhattan and the Bronx, their district attorneys oppose
capital punishment and have never sought an execution.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk and Monroe counties demanded the death penalty in the
highest percentage of cases among counties with at least five
indictments for first-degree murder. The counties also have
contributed four of the six men on death row: three from Suffolk
and one from Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suffolk and Monroe counties are the Texas and Florida of New
York state. They help show that where defendants live is
determining whether they might die,'' said Rochester lawyer Donald
M. Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Relin, Monroe County's district attorney, disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   ''To analogize us with Texas and Florida is absurd in every
sense of the word,'' he said. ''We're not here because we're
looking for ways to give someone the death penalty. We're here
because we're seeking justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics matter because if the state Court of Appeals
finds that the six men now on death row were denied their
constitutional right to equal protection, it could throw out the
capital law and reverse their death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors find the figures problematic. ''I think it
raises a very good issue,'' said Erie County District Attorney
Frank J. Clark, who has asked for the death penalty in one of 10
first-degree murder cases. ''I don't know if I have a definitive
answer to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors who vigorously seek the death penalty say
they're protecting their communities from the most vicious
criminals and believe the state Court of Appeals, which could hear
the appeal of the first death row inmate next year, will find no
unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can have two defendants in different geographical
locations who commit the same crime, and one faces the death
penalty and one doesn't,'' said Batavia lawyer D. Michael Murray,
who has represented four capital defendants. ''That seems to
indicate that we have a death penalty statute that should be
declared unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County District Attorney James M. Catterson Jr. said the
lopsided figures featuring his Long Island county are statistical
blips that will even out as more capital cases go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got to be a sicko if you enjoy the death penalty,'' he
said. ''If you've ever been involved in the process, it's like
combat; you don't want to go back again. But there's no longer a
debate on whether we should have the death penalty. They've given
us the law and it's up to us to enforce it.''
</P>
<P>
   New York hasn't executed anyone since Eddie Lee Mays went to the
electric chair in 1963 for killing a woman in a Harlem tavern
robbery. Despite attempts to bring back capital punishment after
the U.S. Supreme Court lifted a ban in 1976, two successive
Democratic governors - Hugh Carey and Mario Cuomo - repeatedly
vetoed death penalty legislation over two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But George Pataki, a Republican, defeated Cuomo in 1994 with a
pledge to enact a capital law. Pataki signed the law two months
after he was sworn in, making New York the 38th state with the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   New York's capital law allows grand juries to bring charges of
first-degree murder against defendants who commit an intentional
murder accompanied by at least one of 12 aggravating factors, such
as a death during another felony.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have 120 days after arraignment to decide whether to
seek the death penalty. If they do, defendants potentially face a
two-part trial.
</P>
<P>
   If jurors convict a defendant of first-degree murder, they
convene in a penalty phase to decide punishment: life in prison
without the possibility of parole or death by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   When the law was passed, opponents fretted that prosecutors
would apply the law with gleeful abandon to show voters that they
are tough on criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Since the law took effect, prosecutors have sought death for 40
defendants. When opponents compare that figure with 3,794 arrests
for second-degree murder through June 30, they concede that
prosecutors have exhibited restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ''That shows that there definitely has not been a rush, that
district attorneys have been exercising judgment and discretion in
determining whether or not to go for the death penalty,'' said
retired Court of Appeals Judge Stewart F. Hancock Jr. of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hancock believes his former colleagues could overturn the
capital law because of the seeming geographic disproportion in
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Capital defense lawyers in other states have argued
unsuccessfully before the U.S. Supreme Court that geographic
disparity violates sections of the U.S. Constitution that ban cruel
and unusual punishment and guarantee equal protection.
</P>
<P>
   But Hancock believes New York's highest court could decide that
state residents are entitled to more protection under similar
clauses of the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''In interpreting the state constitution, they can give greater
constitutional protection than the U.S. Supreme Court gives. They
can't give less, but they can give more,'' said Hancock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-27-00 1436 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
