<HEADLINE> Thruway offers cheaper gas due to summer subsidy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gas at Thruway rest stops is about a nickel
a gallon cheaper than outside the highway because of a Thruway
Authority program that's subsidizing $900,000 in gas stations'
rent.
</P>
<P>
   The Authority eliminated rent at gas stations to pass on savings
to customers and encourage travel at a time of high fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot cheaper than where we just came from,'' said
Jeffrey Kimball. He and seven people from the Watertown area
stopped at the Guilderland rest stop and filled their van with
regular unleaded priced at $1.569 per gallon. Back home, he said,
similar fuel is $1.71 to $1.75 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers on the Massachusetts Turnpike - where Mass Pike
officials say concession revenues are flat this summer - might find
Mobil gasoline 12 cents a gallon more expensive. In Massachusetts
and New York, toll road stations are able to set rates based on
prices in the off-highway areas of their market.
</P>
<P>
   While summer is coming to an end, it's unclear whether the
subsidy has brought more tourism and traffic, but gasoline
deliveries are up for most of the Thruway's 28 stations - in some
cases markedly.
</P>
<P>
   In June, deliveries rose 13 percent from June 1999, although in
July they rose just 3 percent. However, last year's Woodstock
performance drew thousands of extra motorists, while this year's
June numbers include the Friday of the July 4th weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've seen a lot of increase in travel,'' said Mike Reagan, a
supervisor at the Pattersonville Sunoco. ''We thought it was going
to decrease because of the gas cost increase. I think it's because
the Thruway dropped the price ... Personally, I think that's the
best thing the Thruway's ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant revenues also rose in June, jumping by 7 percent at
HMSHost Corp., the operator of several eateries, to $5.2 million.
McDonald's revenues increased 6.97 percent in June to almost $3.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   But travelers spent less on eateries in July, which saw a
decline of 7.4 percent, to $6.9 million, for HMSHost and about 2.2
percent, to almost $4.1 million, at McDonald's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
