<HEADLINE> Englewood schools asks students to prove residence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ENGLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) - Parents of Englewood public school
students will be asked to prove that their children live in the
city before classes begin or start looking for a new school.
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven months, hundreds of Englewood parents have
found themselves entangled in an aggressive reregistration campaign
initiated by a homeowners group that claimed tax money was being
spent on hundreds of out-of-district students illegally attending
city schools.
</P>
<P>
   School officials want all of the district's 2,770 students to
reregister with proof they live there. So far, only two students
have been found who are not residents, but school board members are
considering offering a bounty of $250 to $300 dollars to people who
turn more in.
</P>
<P>
   Parents of 56 children who graduated in June also will have to
come up with proof - or be held responsible for the tuition of
every year their children spent in the schools. Per-pupil tuition
is about $10,000 for high school, slightly less for elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   ''How could I possibly ever come up with 12 years worth of
tuition?'' Gracey Alexander, the mother of recent graduate Cynthia
Alexander, told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   School district officials say ensuring that all students are
from the city is important, because those who aren't are getting a
free education, further crowding schools and taking teachers' time
away from children of taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe we just need this for a couple of years,'' said board
member David Matthews. ''Sometimes you need a shock to the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have pointed out that the Bergen County city has gone to
great lengths to attract pupils from outside the district. For 15
years, Englewood has fought a court battle to stop the
predominantly white borough of Englewood Cliffs from pulling its
students out of a high school whose enrollment is primarily black
and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing to me that we spend so much money trying to get
students to come here, and here we are spending so much money and
time trying to kick kids out,'' parent Ella Jackson said at a
recent meeting with school board members. ''Do we want in, or do we
want out?''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the effort targets illegal residents and
underprivileged children suspected to be coming from the Paterson,
Union City or the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ''The victims are going to be those immigrants who don't have
documents and are afraid to come forward, and I find that
objectionable,'' said Michael Kaufman, who has two children in the
schools and three who graduated from them. ''It's not like people
are sneaking in from Alpine.''
</P>
<P>
   About 320 families who failed to respond to four letters asking
them for proof of residency will receive letters this week
notifying them that their children will not be allowed to attend
Englewood schools.
</P>
<P>
   Parents have 21 days to appeal the ''de-enrollment,'' during
which time their children can attend classes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-27-00 1515 </TRAILER>
