<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor says school vouchers 'becoming close to a moral issue'  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Citing studies that he says show widespread
support for school vouchers among minority families, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said Sunday he does not understand why people with the
means to send their children to private schools should deny poor
families the same opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vouchers are becoming close to a moral issue,'' Giuliani said.
''A growing number of people ... realize that the best answer for
upward mobility is a good education. The public school system in
general is not providing that.''
</P>
<P>
   About 165,000 people in New York City sought vouchers last year
while only 2,500 were available, Giuliani told reporters outside a
Roman Catholic church where he attended Mass with his newly
appointed police commissioner, Bernard Kerik.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should give them freedom of choice,'' Giuliani said. ''We
supposedly believe in freedom of choice for other things. I don't
understand why politicians oppose freedom of choice for education,
particularly when it affects the poorest children.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was ''not surprised'' by a recent Harvard
University study that found black males performed better in private
schools. Other recent surveys, he said, have shown minorities
favoring by 60 or 70 percent the idea of vouchers for children to
attend private or parochial schools at taxpayer expense.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of vouchers say they offer low-income families a
much-needed alternative, but the concept is opposed by teachers'
unions and other public education advocates who worry vouchers
would hurt poor children by weakening public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George W. Bush backs vouchers for children in
schools that don't show improvement over three years. Democratic
Vice President Al Gore opposes anything that ''diverts funds (from)
public schools.'' His running mate, Connecticut Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, has backed vouchers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall spokeswoman Sunny Mindel said the mayor previously has
spoken out strongly in favor of vouchers, which he originally
opposed before changing his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Kerik said their visit to the Holy Name of Jesus
church in Manhattan, with a mixed congregation that is about half
Hispanic, was part of a continuing effort to improve the police
department's strained relations with minorities.
</P>
<P>
   As he did on a visit last week to a black Baptist church in
Brooklyn, Kerik told parishioners that good community-police
relations were a matter of ''working together,'' which prompted a
burst of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want the police to respect everyone more, then you have
to respect them more,'' said Kerick, who also put in a plug for
police recruitment, saying the department had job opportunities for
applicants with ''integrity and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Everywhere I've gone in the last week, everybody I've talked
to ... everybody's saying the same thing - we have to talk, we have
to listen,'' Kerik said after the service. ''And if people would
just get away from the agenda-seekers, and the people out there
trying to start problems, ... (and) listen to the real people in
the community that do not have agendas, I think there will be a
great working relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Brian Jordan, a Franciscan friar who officiated at the
Spanish-language Mass, said he had invited Kerik after reading that
the new commissioner visited the church in the East New York
section of Brooklyn, where Jordan once lived.
</P>
<P>
   Of the police, Jordan said, ''they have to take responsibility
for some of the problems they've caused, but they have a right to
defend themselves when they are unjustly criticized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
