<DOCNO> APW20000827.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Service: Rains leave state susceptible to new flooding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEPTUNE, N.J. (AP) - Projections by the National Weather Service
indicate New Jersey faces the possibility of widespread floods
should the state be hit by a tropical weather system.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five inches of rain - more than half the annual average -
have fallen in New Jersey from spring to summer, according to the
weather service.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a rain event with 5 inches, we'll have major flooding,
possibly record-setting floods in some places,'' Jim Eberwine, a
meteorologist with the weather service's Mount Holly forecast
office told the Asbury Park Sunday Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we get a 10-inch rain event, we'll see floods of record,''
Eberwine said. Such a rain could raise some rivers to the highest
levels ever, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eberwine said the weather service recently prepared computer
models because of the recent rainfall totals. The 5- and 10-inch
rainfall scenarios are based on a 12-hour time period.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tropical Storm Floyd dumped 6 to 10 inches of rain on
parts of the state within a 12-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Iovino, a meteorologist also at the weather service's Mount
Holly office, said Floyd struck on the heels of a drought. The
state's rivers and reservoirs were substantially below normal
levels last September when Floyd hit. This year, the rivers and
reservoirs are well above normal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a rare case when you're coming out of a summer with
reservoirs at or near capacity,'' Iovino said. Evaporation and
increased water use usually draw down reservoirs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters have predicted as many as 10 major storms could
result from this year's Atlantic hurricane season, which runs from
June through November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
