<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court documents indicate mob boss tried to expand Camden influence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Federal court documents indicate that south
Jersey-Philadelphia mob boss Ralph Natale tried to expand his
influence here even before he started dealing with Mayor Milton
Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Inquirer reported in Sunday's editions that
Natale and several associates met at least twice with Camden
Councilman James Mathes Jr.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents obtained by the newspaper that are part
of two ongoing criminal cases, at one of those meetings, the
councilman and a female friend picked out a $2,000 diamond ring
that was later given to her.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said the offering was part of an effort to
influence Mathes to help award city contracts to businesses linked
with Natale and his associates.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into corruption in Camden resulted in the
indictments of Milan and Natale and nearly a dozen of his
associates. Milan is awaiting trial on federal corruption charges.
Natale has agreed to testify for the government.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reviewed of hundred of pages of FBI memos,
affidavits and partial transcripts of conversations secretly
recorded during the investigation in the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations recorded indicate how the mob intended to provide
shoddy materials and inferior workmanship in the construction deals
in order to increase its profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not building the pyramids,'' Natale said in one
conversation. ''If it only last five years, that's not a problem
... Cosmetically, it'll look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathes served on the city council between 1986 and 1997 and was
council president until December 1995. He refused to discuss the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to talk about it,'' he said. When asked about
the ring, he told the newspaper, ''I've never done anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by The Associated Press to reach Mathes Sunday were
unsuccessful. There was no telephone number listed under his name.
</P>
<P>
   Mathes, who has not been charged in the investigation, now works
as an affirmative action officer for the Camden school system. His
employment records, along with records of contracts awarded by the
Board of Education, were subpoenaed earlier this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
