<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notebook of Clinton's Africa Trip  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   USHAFA, Nigeria (AP) -- President Clinton appeared reluctant at
first, but he ultimately bowed to the will of the village elder
Sunday and donned the flowing robe of Ushafa's royal family.
</P>
<P>
   After touring Ushafa, famous for its pottery, Clinton was
showered with gifts from Chief Mohammadu Baba. Among them was a
flowing cream-colored ''babun riga'' for him, and a two-piece wrap
for his daughter, Chelsea. With the help of two women, Chelsea
eagerly tried on the skirt, called a ''zani,'' and the shoulder
throw, a ''gele.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton watched Chelsea's zeal and under Baba's gentle urging,
he caved. Off came his brown sport jacket, on went the robe, up
went his thumb -- prompting loud cheers of delight from the crowd.
Clinton tried to squeeze on an accompanying blue cap as well, but
it was too small.
</P>
<P>
   The president kept on the robe for a few minutes as he continued
his tour. A dancer in a bright blue striped costume trimmed in
straw leapt and stomped in greeting. As Clinton walked through the
village, a throng of children hovered happily at his knees,
singing: ''We are happy, we are happy to see your face.''
</P>
<P>
   The robe is the second in Clinton's collection. He received --
and wore -- a pale blue robe while visiting a village in Senegal in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   For a few seconds Sunday, Jesse Jackson was president.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was slated to speak ahead of Clinton during a gathering
of Nigerian and American business leaders. The man who introduced
Jackson closed by inadvertently saying, ''I present the president
of the United States ...''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is as good a place as any to be introduced as the
president,'' joked Jackson, who sought the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1984 and 1988. He turned to Clinton and quipped,
''Long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson went on to praise Clinton for being so interested in
Africa, saying, ''His being here is kind of a sonic boom in world
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Because he has blazed a trail, it will never be as it once
was,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's speech, the crowd serenaded him with, ''For He's
a Jolly Good Fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to Nigeria's three major ethnic groups, President
Olusegun Obasanjo gave Clinton three African names.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can now call himself Sodangi, a Hausa name meaning
''lover of people,'' Okoro, the Ibo name for ''man of the people,''
and Omowale, Yoruba for ''child that has returned home.''
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo bestowed the names on Clinton during a state dinner
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very glad to have a Nigerian name,'' Clinton said -- and
asked Obasanjo for a copy of his remarks ''so that when we go out
tomorrow, I can introduce myself properly to the people of your
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not publicly mention the names Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1608 </TRAILER>
