<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow Page Consultants sparks many complaints from businesses  </HEADLINE>
	   By The Associated Press:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yellow Page Consultants, a Glastonbury, Conn. company that
advises businesses on saving telephone pages advertising money, is
facing numerous complaints in Connecticut and Massachusetts of
dishonest sales pitches and meaningless consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses also accuse the company of confusing contract
terms and aggressive collection practices.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen clients have filed complaints with the Connecticut
Department of Consumer Protection; twice that number have
complained to the Attorney General's office, The Hartford Courant
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Superior Court, Yellow Page Consultants is a leader among
business-to-business firms in suing clients who have balked at
paying bills - 160 since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In court records and interviews with The Courant, many clients
charge they were misled into signing a binding contract and learned
- sometimes years later - that they were obligated to pay Yellow
Page Consultants any time they reduced, moved or eliminated a
yellow page ad. The bills came even if the change had nothing to do
with YPC's advice.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the advice amounted to little more than telling them to
shrink their ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''Telling me that a little ad costs less than a big ad is
nothing,'' said Sebastian N. Giuliano, a Middletown lawyer who
represents Omni Home Health Service, a YPC client. ''I can save you
money on gas: Drive less.''
</P>
<P>
   David M. Ford, YPC's founder and president, dismissed complaints
against the company and said he would not discuss them in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to respond to baseless allegations,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said his 10-year-old company has thousands of satisfied
clients and complaints are generated by a tiny fraction of clients
who simply refuse to pay their bills. He said all clients receive
in-depth consulting services.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said the vast majority of yellow page advertisers are
oversold and said his company offers detailed information on how
clients can run smaller ads without losing their effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said almost every client who has accused Yellow Page
Consultants of improper business practices ultimately resolved the
dispute by making a payment to the company. Only a handful have
gone to trial, where judges and juries have been split on the
enforceability of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Among the complaints, Paul Poulin said he rejected YPC's advice
seven years ago to shrink the ads for his East Hartford carpet
cleaning business, and assumed his dealings with YPC were done.
</P>
<P>
   When he shrank one ad and eliminated another, more than two
years after meeting with YPC's salesman, Poulin was sued for more
than $2,600. In a letter to the state Attorney General's office,
his lawyer said Ford threatened to ''bury'' Poulin in legal fees if
he didn't pay.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Ford said the allegation was not true and that
Poulin's lawyer had an unspecified ''ax to grind.'' Poulin said he
settled the case for less than $500.
</P>
<P>
   John Buster, president of Bedworks Inc. in Cambridge, Mass.,
said he made no changes to his yellow page ads. But he received a
bill last year for $28,000, under a contract provision that made
him liable for half the savings he would have realized if he had
used the ads prepared by Yellow Page Consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gay, president of The Jester's Court, a Manchester
banquet hall, said YPC tried to intimidate him into paying a $1,700
bill several years ago. Gay said in a complaint to the Attorney
General's office that his lawyer was told that if Gay fought the
bill, Yellow Page Consultants would sue him and use the proceedings
to expose an embarrassing personal secret.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish I knew what it was,'' Gay said of the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Ford cites praising letters from clients such as Gerry Amodio,
co-owner of Amodio Moving in New Britain. Amodio said he cut his
yellow page bill from $225,000 a year to $168,000, without any
drop-off in calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's office, which for several years has
worked to mediate disputes involving Yellow Page Consultants,
recently revived a broader investigation of the company's business
practices, based on a spate of new complaints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
