<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Photographs Gulf Air Wreckage  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- U.S. Navy divers photographed the sunken
engines and other fractured sections of Gulf Air Flight 072 Sunday,
shooting still pictures and videotapes of the wreckage before it is
lifted from the shallow sea floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''You guys find that other piece I was talking about -- piece
with the shaft? It's around here somewhere ... maybe here,'' one
diver says to his colleagues before bobbing beneath the surface. A
few seconds later, he's back. ''Hey, right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy divers accompanied an investigator from the U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board, all part of the early stages
of the probe into Wednesday's crash of the Airbus A320 that killed
all 143 people aboard. Bahrain, which has close ties with the
United States and is home base to the U.S. Navy's 5th fleet,
appointed NTSB investigator Frank Hilldrup the chief investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The ''black boxes'' -- flight data and cockpit voice recorders --
could provide crucial information in pinpointing why the airliner
nose-dived into the shallow Gulf waters off the coast of Bahrain.
The recorders were expected to arrive at NTSB headquarters in
Washington later Sunday for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim al-Hamer, chairman of the investigating committee, said
the boxes appeared to be in good shape and that his team -- in its
second full day on the job -- has not ruled out any possible causes.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope to learn what happened between the time pilot
Ihsan Shakeeb aborted his landing at Bahrain International Airport
without explanation and 60 seconds later when the plane hit the
sea. Gulf Air's chief pilot Hameed Ali has said the speed and
altitude of Shakeeb's aborted landing would be investigated, but
said no error was spotted in Shakeeb's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a routine autopsy performed Thursday on Shakeeb's
remains had been turned over to investigators, according to Gulf
Air spokesman Chris Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gulf Air Chief Executive Sheik Ahmed bin Saif Al
Nahyan said Sunday the airline had turned over to investigators all
records and files relevant to the crashed Airbus A320 and its crew.
</P>
<P>
   Bahraini Coast Guard divers also were in the water Sunday,
retrieving more personal belongings of those aboard. Temperatures
that topped 104 degrees in the shade combined with stifling
humidity meant teams on the water were being rotated every 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Divers were trying to work quickly to complete their task before
the shifting sand covered debris. Still, Bahraini civil defense
chief Col. James Windsor said he expected the site work to continue
all week.
</P>
<P>
   Though floating debris had been removed soon after the crash so
it wouldn't be swept away with the tides, authorities had been
waiting for the investigation team before removing sunken items.
The Bahraini divers, Windsor said, were retrieving suitcases,
clothing, purses, as well as more human remains.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the bodies has made identifying them
emotionally and practically difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At least five Egyptians were believed to have been misidentified
and mistakenly buried, three of them in Bahrain and two in Saudi
Arabia, Egyptian Embassy spokesman Mohammed al-Tawargy said.
</P>
<P>
   Families of four of them, he said, have decided to leave the
remains where they were when an exhumation attempt found them
already decaying. The family of the fifth was hoping to secure
fingerprint records in Egypt that could be checked against the
remains so they could plan a Christian burial.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be sadly difficult,'' al-Tawargy said. The remains
had been placed into the ground without a coffin in accordance with
Islamic funeral rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of three Egyptians were flown back to Cairo, a day
after 56 sets of remains were returned along with most relatives
who had come to collect them.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven sets of remains had not been identified by Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
