<HEADLINE> Speculation on Kenya Priest's Murder  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Speculation surrounding the death of an
outspoken American priest increased Sunday with local media reports
that documents found on his body linked two Kenyan cabinet
ministers to violent tribal clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John Kaiser had intended to hand the documents over to
a government commission looking into the clashes, which took place
in Rift Valley Province between 1992 and 1997, the independent
Sunday Nation newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the special commission earlier this year,
Kaiser, a Minnesota native who had worked in the East African
nation for 36 years, had already accused two cabinet ministers of
fomenting the bloody clashes. He had said the ministers had stolen
land from those forced to flee the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Neither minister was named in the report.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, the Sunday Nation said an autopsy Saturday
revealed that the 67-year-old priest was shot by a high-velocity
rifle, normally used by police or Kenya Wildlife Service rangers.
His body was found along a highway with a head wound early
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A set of bloodstained fingerprints were also found on the
body,'' the paper quoted a source at Lee Funeral Home, which
carried out the autopsy, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan human rights activists immediately called the death of
Kaiser, a vocal critic of Kenya's human rights record, a political
assassination. The Kenya Human Rights Network said it would set up
an independent citizens' inquiry into the priest's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday Standard, also an independent newspaper, said letters
to the World Bank, government officials and a notice of intention
to sue the Attorney General were among the documents found on his
body.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, President Daniel arap Moi said he was saddened by
the killing. He criticized the politicization of the death during a
public address in the coastal city of Mombasa, the newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police could not be immediately reached to verify the reports,
and there was no independent verification of the information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
