<HEADLINE> Grand jury requests Washington Township mayor's bank records  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - As part of a recently initiated
investigation into land deals in this Gloucester County town, a
federal grand jury has asked to see the bank records of Mayor
Gerald Luongo, according to law enforcement authorities and a
federal document.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena, obtained by The Philadelphia Inquirer, is part of
two investigations - one federal and one state - that focus in part
on a low-income housing project that was the town's first attempt
at providing affordable housing, according to law enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said another facet of the
investigation is a housing deal that led to a $900,000 profit for
several people connected to Luongo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office is prohibited from giving information
about ongoing investigations and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo also declined to comment to the newspaper and referred
questions to his attorney, Carl Poplar. Poplar said his client did
not know that investigators had subpeonaed the bank records.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI began investigating the land deal after town officials
contacted them.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a letter has surfaced that shows a private developer
was carving up planned profits on the land long before the township
bought it with taxpayer money, according to Township Council
President Matthew Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   The Inquirer reported last year that eight investors - four who
had connections to Luongo - bought 28 acres of farmland for
$400,000 then, the same day, sold the parcel to a builder of
low-income housing for $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newspaper, three weeks later the township not
only bought 13 acres of the 28-acre tract for $90,000 more than
builder M. Brad Ingerman had paid for the entire parcel, but also
lent the builder $1.9 million to build low-income housing. The loan
was at 3 percent interest, with no principal or interest due for 32
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ingerman declined to comment to the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
