<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Casual attire to become a no-no at Middlesex County Courthouse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - After Labor Day, employees wearing
denim clothing to work at the Middlesex County Courthouse could get
a dressing-down.
</P>
<P>
   The courthouse's 580 workers were notified by memos included in
recent paychecks the manner of dress is going more formal as of
Sept. 5, The Star-Ledger of Newark reported in Sunday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Robert Longhi, the assignment judge for
Middlesex County, felt employees should dress professionally.
Courthouse officials said the policy is aimed at ensuring a
dignified, professional atmosphere at the courthouse complex.
</P>
<P>
   That means jeans, shorts, shirts without collars, sweat pants or
clothing bearing sports and corporate logos will become out of
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort will too, says Henry Crawn, 29, who often wears jeans
and a T-shirt to work in the 37-year-old building where he is a
judiciary clerk. Crawn said the building's air conditioning
frequently fails, and temperatures rise in the summertime.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's leaving me in a situation where I'm going to go out and
have to purchase more clothes,'' Crawn told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the most part, I sit in a cubicle, and nobody sees me,''
he said. ''How I dress shouldn't affect my work productivity at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers who violate the dress policy may be sent home to change
and could risk having the time deducted from their vacation days.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with unions representing courthouse workers consider
the policy unnecessary and cite concerns about the expense of
workers having to buy new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Some union representatives say the manner of dress should be
flexible and based on the type of work employees do. The
Communications Workers of America Local 1034, which represents 20
computer technicians and other staff, filed a grievance, calling
the issue something that should be negotiated in a labor contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
