<HEADLINE> Cardinals 7, Braves 2  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The St. Louis Cardinals finally showed they could
win a series at Turner Field, and the Atlanta Braves were left
clinging to the slimmest of leads in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile pitched an eight-hitter and the NL Central-leading
Cardinals scored three runs in both the seventh and eighth innings,
beating Atlanta 7-2 Sunday for their first series victory at the
stadium since it opened in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis took three of four games from the Braves, also winning
their first season series (4-3) since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the New York Mets defeated Arizona 2-1 to pull within
a game of Atlanta. It's the smallest margin since July 1, when the
Braves also led by a game. The Braves, going for their ninth
straight division championship, have held at least a share of first
since April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch was delayed 2 hours, 32 minutes by rain, marking
the second time in the series that a game was held up more than two
hours because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta starter John Burkett allowed only two hits through six
innings, leaving with a 2-1 lead, but St. Louis thrived against the
Braves' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg (2-3) surrendered the lead by giving up three
runs in the seventh, including a two-run double by Placido Polanco.
The next inning, Mike Remlinger gave up Mike Matheny's two-run
single before Polanco followed with another double, driving in his
third run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kile (15-9) needed only 102 pitches for his fourth complete game
of the season. He also became St. Louis' second 15-game winner, a
day after Garrett Stephenson got there first.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves jumped ahead 2-0 in the third, thanks to a pair of
perfectly placed hits. Walt Weiss doubled to the gap in
right-center, the ball dropping between Jim Edmonds and J.D. Drew.
Then, Burkett beat out a broken-bat blooper that just cleared the
infield dirt before it was fielded by second baseman Fernando Vina.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett's hit scored Reggie Sanders from third, giving the
Atlanta pitcher his first RBI since 1996. Rafael Furcal followed
with a sacrifice fly that brought home Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett was perfect through three innings, but he plunked Vina
with a pitch leading off the fourth and it wound up costing the
Atlanta starter his only run. Vina moved to third with two outs and
scored when Craig Paquette barely beat out a slow roller between
the mound and third-base line.
</P>
<P>
Notes: St. Louis began the day with a 7&AMP;frac12;-game lead over Cincinnati
in the Central. ... Braves CF Andruw Jones didn't play, ending a
301-game streak that was second-longest in the majors behind Sammy
Sosa. .... Cardinals C Carlos Hernandez left the game in the fifth
inning with a lower back sprain. ... Burkett's RBI was his first
since May 3, 1996, when he played for Florida. He spent the past
three years in the American League. ... St. Louis had seven hits
over the final three innings against Ligtenberg, Remlinger and Gabe
Molina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
