<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Scaled Back  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS TOMLINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- Mediators trying to end Burundi's
seven-year civil war were unlikely to work out a cease-fire before
President Clinton's visit Monday and worked for a less ambitious
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Former South African President Nelson Mandela had set Monday as
the deadline for an agreement to stop the fighting between the
Tutsi-dominated government and Hutu rebels. Plans called for
Clinton and leaders of 12 African nations to witness the signing
ceremony Monday evening in this northern Tanzanian town.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, however, have avoided tying Clinton's
Arusha visit to a signing. They say only that the president, who
was flying from Nigeria early Monday, wants to show his support for
Mandela's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to go to Arusha was made irrespective of whether
or not there was to be a signing,'' Susan Rice, assistant secretary
of state for African affairs, said at a news conference in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Burundian and Western diplomats close to the Burundi talks
admitted Sunday that a cease-fire, the Tutsis' key demand, could
not be reached. Talks were going into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Sunday night, gunfire and tracer bullets lit the sky
over Burundi's capital as Hutu rebels attacked one of Bujumbura's
suburbs on the eve of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Gasenyi, about five miles from the city center,
lasted about an hour. By midnight Sunday, the city was calm, though
nervous soldiers and police patrolled the streets. Most residents
stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time the rebels, who are attacking from
hide-outs in the hills surrounding the lakeside capital, have
launched an assault on Bujumbura. No report on casualties was
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leaders were still boycotting the peace talks in Arusha.
Senior Burundian officials said there were reports that rebel
leaders may be secretly in Arusha, ready to join the talks at the
last minute, but there was no confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a breakthrough, negotiators hoped for a limited
agreement on issues such as the ethnic breakdown of a future
national assembly and how Hutus would be eventually integrated into
the military
</P>
<P>
   The agreement may also include a commitment by the two sides to
seek a cease-fire to the conflict that has killed more than 200,000
people, mostly civilians, since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Western diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said a political agreement would allow Mandela to narrow the number
of groups involved in the negotiations and then focus solely on a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Tutsi political parties, seven Hutu parties, President
Pierre Buyoya's government and the Tutsi army have been discussing
a peace agreement for more than two years and there was a
heightened sense of urgency Sunday ahead of the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the usual pre-agreement panic. They are now getting down
to serious negotiations,'' said one Western observer. The observer,
who did not want to be named, added that a 167-page draft produced
by the mediators was being used in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   While the power-sharing agreement appeared to take shape Sunday,
the lack of progress on a cease-fire threatened to derail the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya repeatedly has said that without an end to the attacks by
Hutu rebels, he cannot sign a power-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Tutsi extremists in the tiny central African country have
threatened to stage a coup if they perceive an agreement as giving
away too much.
</P>
<P>
   A small Tutsi elite has controlled most of Burundi's government
and industries since independence in 1962. A Hutu won the first,
and only, democratic election in 1993, but was assassinated three
months later by Tutsi paratroopers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Tutsis have controlled the political and economic
life in Burundi, while Hutu rebels operating from bases outside the
country have fought for the restoration of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Many Burundian Tutsis, however, fear they will meet the same
fate as Rwanda's Tutsi minority, which in 1994 were victims of a
Hutu government-orchestrated genocide that left more than 500,000
people dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1857 </TRAILER>
