<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pearl Jam Urges Safety at Concerts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- After being horrified by a fatal
stampede at one of their performances, Pearl Jam is taking steps to
avoid another tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The band has asked fans planning to attend a concert at the
Saratoga Performing Arts Center to leave blankets at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause, but we have
witnessed a number of injuries as a result of blankets being used
as trampolines at concerts,'' said Kelly Curtis, manager for the
grunge rock group.
</P>
<P>
   Small beach towels and ponchos were suggested as alternatives to
blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam requested the precautionary blanket ban two months
after nine fans died in a frenzied crush at a concert in Denmark.
After Pearl Jam's 1992 show at the Saratoga center, metal barriers
were installed to prevent stage rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the company that manages the center's
outdoor rock shows banned blankets, but backed down after a public
outcry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1908 </TRAILER>
