<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Cut Pederson, 16 Others  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles released quarterback
Doug Pederson, who started nine games last season, as they trimmed
their roster to the NFL limit of 53 players Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, who had not started an NFL game before he was signed
by the Eagles as an unrestricted free agent prior to the 1999
season, was used as a mentor to aid in the development of Donovan
McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb is now the starter for the Eagles; Pederson is out of a
job.
</P>
<P>
   ''With having three veteran quarterbacks, and with the
improvement of the young quarterbacks, along with Doug's desire to
play, we decided it was mutually beneficial for Doug,'' head coach
Andy Reid said. ''There's not enough money to pay Doug for what he
did for us last year. This is the best thing for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, who has drawn interest from Cleveland, had drawn boos
at Veterans Stadium, and even in the preseason every incomplete
pass was greeted by catcalls, though Reid downplayed the idea that
the fans' unhappiness played into the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, the development of quarterbacks Koy Detmer and
Ron Powlus, who joined the Eagles after a stint in NFL Europe, made
Pederson expendable. The Eagles attempted to trade Pederson but
were not able to work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said Detmer and Pederson were virtually even on the depth
chart. Detmer, now the No. 2 quarterback behind McNabb, signed a
three-year contract extension Sunday that keeps him an Eagle
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a good mentality that relief pitchers need,'' said
Reid. ''He doesn't need a lot of reps to get ready. He knows the
system. We'll be fine there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 1909 </TRAILER>
