<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton labels Senate opponent ''Bush-Lite''  </HEADLINE>
By REAGAN HAYNES
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, N.Y. (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton pressed her attack
Sunday on Republican Senate rival Rick Lazio's tax-cut plan,
calling it a ''tax scheme'' and saying the congressman was trying
to be ''Bush-Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lazio took his fund-raising bandwagon to the first
lady's new hometown in Westchester County, a move designed to
highlight her lack of New York roots.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's second day campaigning with her mother, Dorothy
Rodham, an apparent effort on her part to stress her own family
values which have come under question because of her support for
her husband through the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   At two upstate venues, Clinton slammed Lazio, saying the Long
Island Republican congressman, who has been in Congress for eight
years, had voted eight times for budgets that would hurt New York.
She added the state already does not get its fair share from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, he tried this week to be Bush-Lite,'' she told
crowds of a couple hundred people at stops in Kingston and in
Newburgh.
</P>
<P>
   In the first lady's adopted hometown of Chappaqua, Lazio agreed
that New York gets shorted by Washington but laid the blame at the
feet of President Clinton and took a familiar dig at Hillary
Clinton's recent move to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am delighted to be here in Chappaqua, in my home state, in
my back yard,'' Lazio said at one of four fund-raisers he was
scheduled to attend Sunday. ''We're here to talk about ... the
basic inequity of sending $15 billion more to Washington than New
York gets back. It's at its worst point now, ever, under the
Clinton administration and we need to address that.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiar themes arose in Clinton's stop, as well. She reminded
the crowd of Lazio's four-year service to former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich as deputy whip, asking if it was mainstream to vote for
''Republican budgets that would have slashed $270 million from
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has traveled the state aboard his campaign bus called
''The Mainstream Express.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If you try to match his rhetoric and his record, things just
don't add up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said the ''tax scheme'' Lazio released last week didn't
add up and his cost figure of $776 billion over 10 years was too
low. She said the real cost was more than $1 trillion, a price the
country might not be able to afford and edging up on Texas Gov.
George W. Bush proposed $1.3 trillion tax-cut proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The New York Daily News, Newsday, other experts say the real
cost would be over one trillion dollars,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's own tax-cut plan is at about the same level as Vice
President Al Gore's - in the neighborhood of $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Maurice Hinchey introduced Clinton first in Kingston
and later in Newburgh, calling her one of the best women living in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When she wasn't attacking her opponent, Clinton said she would
support scholarships for those who will teach for four years and
work to ensure health coverage for all.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also told supporters she would strive to address
the national debt, save social security, modernize medicare and
give targeted tax cuts to working families. She did not mention how
she planned to pay for her plans, only that she would fight to get
more money from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-27-00 1925 </TRAILER>
