<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State to review homeowners' claims of rip-off  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLETOWN, N.Y. (AP) - A state housing agency will review
homeowners' claims that they are paying more than advertised to
live in problem plagued condominiums partially paid for with state
money.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the Spring Hollow II condominiums told the Times
Herald-Record of Middletown that kitchen cabinets fell from the
walls, grass and weeds grew through the concrete floor, pipes leak,
doors don't close, windows leak and railings wobble.
</P>
<P>
   Added to those woes, the homeowners say they spent nearly twice
as much for their condominiums - about $110,000 - as the local real
estate market commands and pay $300 to $400 more per month than
expected. Some of the homeowners are paying $1,200 a month for the
condos assessed at $60,500.
</P>
<P>
   The project was funded in part by the state Affordable Housing
Corporation, which loaned each homeowner $25,000 toward the
purchase of the condo, built by Upper West Side developer Marco
Ricotta.
</P>
<P>
   The office of state Housing Finance Agency CEO Stephen J. Hunt
declined to answer specific questions from the Record but issued a
statement on Aug. 22 defending the Affordable Housing Corporation's
Affordable Home Ownership Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it recently became aware of ''information about
construction defects,'' and once it completes a review would
''explore the appropriate remedies in an effort to resolve the
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricotta declined to answer questions from the newspaper. His
lawyer referred questions to another lawyer who was out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got took,'' said home buyer Anthony Hodge of 37 Woodlake
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Some owe mortgage companies $90,000 or more but resales at
Spring Hollow's first phase range from $40,000 to $77,000. The
average selling price of a condo in Middletown was $56,300 in the
first half of 1999, $63,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Thomas Kirwan of Newburgh said the grant program
should be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sounds like this (developer) blew one by the state,'' he said.
''It's an awful waste of taxpayer money, in addition to these
people getting screwed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
