<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Cut Seven Players  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The Chargers cut wide receiver Charlie Jones
and made seven other roster moves Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, drafted in the fourth round out of Fresno State in 1996,
was the Chargers' top punt returner this summer. But the team was
expected to cut him after trading an undisclosed late-round draft
choice to the Miami Dolphins for Nate Jacquet earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Jones played 54 games with the Chargers, making
129 catches for 1,736 yards and nine touchdowns. His best season
was 1998, when he had 46 receptions for a team-high 699 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a dislocated hip in the preseason last year and had
only 10 catches for 90 yards and nine punt returns for 93 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cutting Jones, the Chargers released six other
players: guard Wilbert Brown; cornerback Shad Criss; linebackers
Michael Hamilton, Shannon Taylor and Deon Humphrey; and center
Jason Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the team said it had reached an injury settlement
with linebacker Richard Hogans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
