<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars' Keep Searcy Spot Open  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The Jacksonville Jaguars will keep a
roster spot open while Pro Bowl right tackle Leon Searcy
rehabilitates the injury to the tendon above his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Coughlin made the decision this weekend. He said
conversations with doctors made him believe Searcy can return by
late November, when the Jaguars figure to be in the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've talked to players, I've watched Leon work out, and I've
talked with him at great length,'' Coughlin said Sunday after the
Jaguars trimmed their roster to 53 players.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm cautiously optimistic. I believe he'll be prepared to play
in late November.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Jaguars placed Searcy on injured reserve to save a
roster spot, he would have been lost for the season. Searcy said he
waged a full-fledged campaign with Coughlin last week for a spot on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-year veteran tore his quadriceps in one-on-one drills
July 24.
</P>
<P>
   ''The healing is a lot further along than the doctor expected,''
he said recently. ''His statement to me was, 'It would be crazy if
you go on IR.' It was real positive, real uplifting, and I'm going
to run with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin will monitor Searcy's progress and said he will have to
meet deadlines on several milestones during the rehab process. One
of the key points will come after the eighth game of the season,
Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The coach also said other injuries could dictate a change.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a situation that's totally in Leon's control,''
Coughlin said. ''This team has to play, play well and play without
injuries for everything to work out. If we have too many nicks that
go two or three weeks and we don't have enough players to practice,
those circumstances will be difficult to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
