<HEADLINE> Seahawks Cut Peterson, 14 Others  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- Kicker Todd Peterson was among 15 players
released by the Seattle Seahawks on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, a six-year NFL veteran who was third in the league in
scoring among kickers last season, was released partly for
financial reasons. Kris Heppner, a free-agent from Montana, will
take Peterson's job, at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson hit 34 of 40 field goal attempts last season and had
134 points overall. He has made all 181 of his career point-after
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson attempted only two field goals in preseason games -- a
miss from 52 yards and a successful 22-yarder -- while Heppner's
only preseason attempt was good from 28 yards out. Heppner also
twice outdueled Peterson in post-practice contests, during which
both kickers alternated attempts at varying distances.
</P>
