<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Scrambling for School Leaders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The nation's second-largest school district
is short 40 principals with just two weeks to go before classes
begins, and the district's new superintendent is calling on retired
administrators to step in.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the top posts remain open at 31 elementary schools and
seven middle and high schools in the Los Angeles Unified School
District.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a principal shortage, and we've had it for two years
in a row,'' Superintendent Roy Romer told Sunday's Los Angeles
Times. ''Half of it is due to retirement. The rest is due to the
fact that principals are moving to central offices because of the
new opportunities and pay increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the shortage stems from a reorganization of the
711,000-student district which created 11 sub-districts and a
number of new administrative posts.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our decentralization, we took the opportunity to get new
blood into management, which is a good thing,'' Romer said.
''What's bad, is that it creates a vacancy we need to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Some schools anticipate being without a permanent principal
until October.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said the district is ''putting intensive work'' into
professional development academies and other career training
programs for teachers who want to move into administrative
positions.
</P>
<P>
   Until the positions are filled, interim principals will be
expected to take up the slack by coordinating curriculum and by
developing and launching reform programs.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Brent, president of the Associated Administrators of Los
Angeles union, said some teachers and parents are concerned about
the responsibilities being placed on unqualified temporary
replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need strong principals in place when schools need them
most,'' Brent said. ''Not people who don't know how to organize a
school, or who are without experience in dealing with parents, or
who are easily intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   California also has struggled to get enough teachers into its
growing schools; it expects to need 300,000 additional teachers
over the next decade alone. In an effort to ease that shortage,
Gov. Gray Davis last month approved more than $2.4 billion in
educational incentives, including higher starting pay and better
benefits, to draw teachers and keep them.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles school: http://www.lausd.k12.ca.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 2107 </TRAILER>
