<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressBunny Austin:
<TEXT>
<P>
   COULSDON, England (AP) -- Henry ''Bunny'' Austin, who teamed with
Fred Perry to win four consecutive Davis Cup finals in a golden era
of British tennis, died Saturday. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Austin's partnership with Perry, who won the Wimbledon singles
title three years in a row between 1934-36, was invincible in four
successive Davis Cup competitions.
</P>
<P>
   They ended a streak of six straight French triumphs 3-2 at
Roland Garros in 1933. Then came 4-1 and 5-0 triumphs over the
United States at Wimbledon in 1934-35, followed by a 3-2 beating of
Australia in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   He went to live in the United States with his wife in 1938,
served as a private in the U.S. Army and did not return to Britain
until 1961.
James L. George:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- James L. George, a retired Navy officer and
writer who was an authority on natural security affairs, died
Thursday of cancer. He was 60.
</P>
<P>
   George wrote extensively on naval issues and was the author of
''History of Warships,'' published in 1998, and ''U.S. Navy in the
1990s: Alternatives for Action,'' published in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the U.S. contributing editor of U.S. Naval Forces,
published in Germany, and a commentary writer for Defense News,
Navy Times and other publications covering the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a staffer for House and Senate committees,
specializing in national security issues, and served in the Reagan
administration as assistant director for multilateral affairs at
the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
Karen Potter:
</P>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Karen Potter, who spent a decade
covering Texas politics for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram and later
worked as the managing editor/features at the Times Union in
Albany, died Saturday. She was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Potter died after battling a rare form of bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fort Worth, Texas, paper, she became the youngest state
Capitol bureau chief at 30 and won numerous journalism awards for
her investigative work.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the Times Union in 1995, Potter produced an
award-winning series on domestic violence, nurtured in-depth
projects on autism and hospice care, introduced long human-interest
narratives told in short chapters and encouraged a whimsical take
on celebrity, popular culture and fashion trends.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include her husband and daughter.
Cal Stoll:
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cal Stoll, the former Minnesota football
coach who had a heart transplant 13 years ago, died Friday. He was
76.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll had been ill for more than a month as heart trouble caused
damage to other vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll was 39-39 at Minnesota from 1972-78. One of his top
players was quarterback Tony Dungy, now the head coach of the NFL's
Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll's biggest win came in 1977, when the Gophers beat
top-ranked Michigan 16-0. Minnesota also beat UCLA and Washington
that season, and lost to Maryland in the Hall of Fame Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll was 15-17 at Wake Forest from 1969-71.
Douglas Allen Woody:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Douglas Allen Woody, a former bassist for the
Allman Brothers Band, was found dead in a motel, police said
Sunday. He was 44.
</P>
<P>
   A chambermaid in the Marriott Courtyard Motel in Queens found
Woody's body at 10:30 a.m. Saturday, police said. There were no
visible signs of trauma, and the cause of death is still unknown,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Woody joined the Allman Brothers Band as a bassist in 1989. He
left with slide guitarist Warren Haynes in April 1997, and the two
formed a musical trio called Gov't Mule, with drummer Matt Apts.
The band released several albums.
</P>
<P>
   Woody lived in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
</TEXT>
