<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Seeks Soldiers' Release in Africa  </HEADLINE>
By AUDREY WOODS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Efforts to win the release of 11 captive British
soldiers in Sierra Leone have begun, in cooperation with the
government of the ravaged West African country, the British
government said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials said the leader of the British team, which was
captured Friday, had been in contact and had said all were being
fed and well-treated.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in early Monday editions of several newspapers said the
government had sent a special military team to Sierra Leone to
stand by in case they were needed for a rescue. Two police hostage
negotiators reportedly also went along.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry declined to comment on any military
mission. But it said a team of ''varying makeup'' had been sent to
help win the men's freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident we can secure their release through
discussion with their captors, and the team was sent in order to
aid that process,'' a spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 soldiers from the Royal Irish Regiment lost contact with
their base on Friday around the towns of Masiaka and Forudugu, 45
miles east of Freetown, force commander Brig. Gordon Hughes said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter search failed to find any trace of them. A later
radio message from the group had indicated they were being held
against their will, a Ministry of Defense spokesman said in London.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have made contact with those who appear to be holding'' the
men, a Defense Ministry spokesman said, but ''discussions are at a
very early stage.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that Britain was ''working closely with the government
of Sierra Leone to try to bring this to a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In Freetown, the Sierra Leone capital, British force spokesman
Capt. John Price confirmed that ''efforts are still going on to
secure their safe release. Negotiations are going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The British troops were stationed at Benguema, 25 miles east of
Freetown, where British instructors are training Sierra Leonean
army recruits. They were accompanied by a government soldier, who
was acting as their guide and was also believed to have been
captured.
</P>
<P>
   The troops disappeared in an area occupied by a small and
ruthless renegade faction of fighters known as the West Side Boys,
Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Until June, the West Side Boys were part of a fragile
pro-government alliance fighting Sierra Leone's feared
Revolutionary United Front rebels. But the faction fell out with
the authorities after allegedly attacking other pro-government
fighters and carrying out a spree of carjackings, robberies and
rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sierra Leone's civil war began in 1991, the rebels have
killed and maimed tens of thousands of people in an attempt to gain
control of the government and the country's lucrative
diamond-mining regions. They have abandoned three peace treaties,
the latest signed July last year.
</P>
<P>
   Britain sent 1,000 soldiers to Freetown when the RUF rebels
restarted the conflict in May. The rebels seized 500 U.N.
peacekeepers and advancing toward the capital. While the troops
ostensibly went to evacuate foreigners and secure the airport,
their presence did much to stabilize the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages were eventually released and a successful rescue
operation was mounted to free 233 other U.N. troops surrounded in
rebel territory. A ragtag alliance of pro-government forces, backed
by Britain, meanwhile began pushing the rebels away from Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   When the British forces withdrew in mid-June, they left behind
soldiers to train Sierra Leone army recruits. Britain has also
donated arms and equipment and sent military advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 2138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
