<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes from Sunday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Devil Rays-Orioles:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays placed RHP Tanyon Sturtze on the
15-day DL with a strained ribcage muscle. The injury occurred
Saturday. ... His place on the roster was filled by RHP Tony Fiore,
who pitched three scoreless innings Sunday in his major league
debut. ... The Devil Rays went 5-8 on their 13-game road trip. They
also fell farther behind Baltimore in their bid to leave last place
in the AL East for the first time since April 16.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: OF Albert Belle was rested Sunday, ending his string
of 232 straight games. He last sat June 11, 1999. ... SS Melvin
Mora has hit in 21 of 29 games with the Orioles. ... Mike Kinkade
got two hits in his final game before joining the U.S. Olympic
baseball team. ... RHP Mike Trombley worked a perfect eighth inning
and has fanned five of the last six batters he's faced.
Blue Jays-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays are hoping for a lift out of Joey
Hamilton in September as the right-hander comes back from rotator
cuff surgery. Hamilton has allowed seven hits in 12 innings over
his first two starts since coming off the disabled list on Aug. 19,
and the Blue Jays hope he can give staff ace David Wells some help
down the stretch in the wild-card race. ... The rest of the
schedule would seem to bolster Toronto's playoff hopes. Toronto has
17 of its final 29 games at home, and the Blue Jays have won 10 of
their last 14 at SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers hoped to have Darren Oliver back in the
rotation in September, but the left-hander's rehab from weakness in
his throwing shoulder has been up and down. Oliver allowed seven
runs and 10 hits over 4 2-3 innings in Saturday night's start for
Double-A Tulsa. Oliver returned to Arlington on Sunday and his
status will be evaluated over the next few days. Oliver has been on
the disabled list since Aug. 1 and his last victory was May 31. ...
Injured C Ivan Rodriguez had a smaller cast placed on his broken
right thumb and is currently in his native Puerto Rico visiting
relatives. He will return to Arlington on Wednesday to have team
medical personnel check on how well the thumb is healing.
Red Sox-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: The Red Sox failed to win the 2000 season series against
Kansas City after dominating the Royals the previous two years. In
1998 and '99 the Red Sox went 16-5 against KC. ... SS Nomar
Garciaparra's three hits Saturday night made him the third player
in Red Sox history to record 50 multihit games in four consecutive
seasons. The others were Ted Williams and Wade Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals have begun hyping OF Mark Quinn for AL
rookie of the year. An 11th-round choice in the June 1995 draft,
Quinn ranks among rookie leaders in home runs, average, doubles,
extra-base hits, total bases and outfield assists. The team came
under media criticism for not trying to make Quinn's case. ...
After starting the year 2-11 on the road, the Royals have gone
27-27 away from home.
Tigers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Todd Jones blew his third save this season in 39
chances Sunday. ... Starter Dave Mlicki pitched in a rehab
assignment Sunday at Class-A West Michigan. Mlicki is recovering
from a severe sinus infection, which required surgery. ... The
Tigers are attempting to become the first team since the 1996 Red
Sox to finish above .500 after being 14 games under at one point in
the season. ... With four games left in August, the Tigers have
ensured themselves of their third straight winning month. The last
time Detroit had winning records in three straight months was in
1988. ... Detroit pitchers issued 10 walks Sunday. Nelson Cruz
walked four in 2 1-3 innings, after walking just six in 33 previous
innings this year.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Minnesota evened its record against Detroit at the
Metrodome at 56-56. ... OF Matt Lawton, who hit leadoff Sunday,
batted third in 121 of 122 previous games he started. He batted
sixth once.
Yankees-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: OF Paul O'Neill was not in the lineup because of his
sore right hip pointer. He has missed four games, and could miss
the Seattle series as well. ... RHP Ramiro Mendoza will throw from
the mound Monday or Tuesday. Mendoza has been on the 15-day DL
since July 30 with tendinitis in his right shoulder. ... 2B Chuck
Knoblauch, who was hit by a pitch on his left knee in a minor
league rehab assignment Friday, will get a couple more days off,
then get sent to Triple-A Columbus to continue his rehab. ... Torre
responded to a published report that he was on the critical list to
return as manager next season by saying ''I may retire, or I may
not retire. Let's see what they print about that. I haven't said
anything and I don't know where they get that stuff.'' Torre said
he has made no plans either way. ''I don't feel any different than
I did at this time last year,'' he said. ''I'm very content. My
wife wants me to retire right now, but she won't force me, and I
still have that fire in my belly. When it stops being fun, that's
when I'll stop.''
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: 1B Jason Giambi got the day off Sunday and will try to
get an MRI done on his sore left shoulder either Monday or Tuesday.
''He's a little sore, so we're going to be on the safe side,'' A's
manager Art Howe said. A's trainer Larry Davis said the MRI wasn't
critical and that it would be done ''if there was time. The results
would help us manage his injury on a daily basis.'' ... RHP Jon
Ratliff was recalled from Triple-A Sacramento and will pitch out of
the bullpen. Ratliff has pitched eight years in the minors, in the
Chicago Cubs and Atlanta Braves' organizations before signing as a
free agent with the A's this year. ''With Omar (Olivares) going so
long yesterday, we needed somebody who could give us some
innings,'' Howe said. ''He's been one of our most consistent
starters at Sacramento this year.'' Ratliff was 8-3 with a 3.02 ERA
in 17 starts for the Rivercats. He also had one save. ''He was
definitely on our list for September,'' Howe said. ''He's just up a
little earlier.'' ... OF Eric Byrnes was optioned back to
Sacramento to make room on the 25-man roster. Byrnes appeared in
two games for the A's since making his major league debut on
Tuesday in Cleveland. He had two hits in six at bats. ... LHP Rich
Sauveur was designated for assignment to make room for Ratliff on
the 40-man roster.
White Sox-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: SS Jose Valentin, who didn't start for the second
straight game because of an inflammation in his pelvic area,
grounded out in the eighth as a pinch-hitter and had his
career-high 13-game hitting streak broken Sunday. He remained in
the game at shortstop and flied out in the ninth. ... RHP Sean Lowe
made his seventh career start and second in five days. ... DH Frank
Thomas was 1-for-10 with three walks in the series. In six games at
Safeco Field this season, he was 1-for-20. Said Thomas: ''It's just
one of those things. It's nice to be getting out of here.'' ...
Chicago won the season series from Seattle 7-5. It's the first
season series the White Sox have won from the Mariners since 1994,
when they went 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: 3B Carlos Guillen committed his team-leading 15th error
of the season in his 64th game. ... Sunday's crowd of 45,525 was
the second-largest in 107 games at Safeco Field. The largest was
45,552 on opening day this season. ... Freddy Garcia's eight
innings Sunday was his longest outing of the season. His previous
longest start was seven. ... Seattle OF Rickey Henderson walked
once Sunday, giving him 2,046 for his career. He's either 10 or 16
walks shy of Babe Ruth's career record of 2,062 or 2,056, depending
on the record book that is being used.
Indians-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Of the major-league low 38 unearned runs allowed by
the Indians, seven have come with Chuck Finley, Sunday's starter,
on the mound. ... Kenny Lofton, one of baseball's premier leadoff
hitters, has only occasionally batted out of the No. 1 spot this
season for the first time since 1992. On those occasions he's
hitting .381 (16-for-42). ... Jim Thome observed his 30th birthday
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels began Sunday's game one Tim Salmon homer
away from becoming the first team in AL history with a quartet of
30-homer men. Mo Vaughn, who has 138 strikeouts, could break Reggie
Jackson's 1982 team record of 156 strikeouts, and Troy Glaus (131)
might break Bobby Knoop's 1966 record of 144 strikeouts by a
right-handed batter. ... It was business as usual for Troy Percival
when he came off the DL by pitching an inning Saturday night and
giving up a two-run homer to Travis Fryman. Percival is 0-7, with a
9.55 ERA in his career against the Indians, and has a total of 20
losses against all other teams. ...The Angels have neither won nor
lost more than two straight since opening August with five
consecutive losses.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Dodgers-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: OF Bruce Aven posted his second career two-homer
game and first since June 13, 1999, when he did so for the Florida
Marlins against the New York Mets. ... RHP Kevin Brown, who stayed
in his hotel room the first two days of the series to recuperate
from the flu, rejoined the team Sunday. Manager Davey Johnson said
Brown would start Monday against Milwaukee. ... OF Gary Sheffield,
however, remained in Los Angeles, also sick with the flu. Johnson
said he hoped Sheffield could rejoin the team in Milwaukee. ... RHP
Darren Dreifort was moved back a day for extra rest and will start
Thursday, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: LF Rondell White is out for the year after dislocating
his left shoulder sliding headfirst into second base Saturday.
White, who hit .328 in 19 games with the Cubs, finished with an
eight-game hitting streak. He will not need surgery. Manager Don
Baylor said he advocates sliding feet first. ''A lot of bad things
can happen (when they slide headfirst),'' Baylor said. ... OF
Roosevelt Brown was called up from Triple-A Iowa to take White's
spot and homered in his first at-bat. Baylor said he'll split
playing time in left between Gary Matthews Jr., Roosevelt Brown and
Brant Brown. Asked if the Cubs might call up top prospect Corey
Patterson from Double-A West Tenn to fill the gap, Baylor said,
''Absolutely not.''
Astros-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Tony Eusebio doubled twice and hit his seventh homer to
extend his career-best hitting streak to 23 games, tying the
Astros' team record set by Art Howe in 1981, and matched by Luis
Gonzalez in 1997. ... Scott Elarton pitched his second career
complete game for his team-leading 15th win, extending his personal
winning streak to five games. Elarton, who also pitched a complete
game against Montreal on Aug. 6, has not lost on the road since
June 16 at San Francisco. ... Jeff Bagwell's RBI grounder in the
first gave him 31 RBIs in August, tying the team record for RBIs in
a month he already shared with Derek Bell. Bagwell and Bell both
had 31 RBIs in July 1995. Bagwell also drove in 31 runs in May
1996.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Tony Armas Jr. allowed seven hits and three runs in 3
2-3 innings in his first rehab start for Triple-A Ottawa. Armas,
who threw 41 of 58 pitches for strikes, walked one and struck out
three. ... Montreal has lost five of six and 14 of 17 overall. The
Expos have won just twice in their last 16 games at Olympic
Stadium.
Reds-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Pokey Reese, who missed the last nine games with a
strained hamstring, entered the lineup in the fifth inning to
replace SS Barry Larkin. ... Larkin has eight hits in 17 at bats
(.471).
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Mark Smith's double was his 11th pinch-hit this season,
tied for third in the Marlins' record book. ... The two teams
combined for five intentional walks Sunday, tying the high in the
majors this season. ... Mike Redmond went 0-for-2 and is in a
1-for-15 slump.
Rockies-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: The Rockies finished 19-22 in Three Rivers Stadium,
which will be demolished early next year. ... LHP Brian Bohanon
pitched his first complete game of the season Sunday in his third
appearance in a week. He lasted six innings Monday in losing to
Atlanta 7-4, then pitched one-third of an inning a night later in
the 12-inning game in which C Brent Mayne was the winning pitcher.
... 1B Todd Helton went 4-for-10 in the Rockies' three-game sweep
of Pittsburgh. His two-hit game Sunday was his 54th multiple-hit
game this season. Helton said, ''I felt good, I felt like I let it
go. The past few days, I've been so conscious of not swinging at
bad pitches, but I just decided to let it go and see what happens.
I got here by being aggressive and it felt good.'' ... The Rockies
have won six of eight and are two games over .500 for the first
time since July 19.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Pirates pitchers retired the side in order only once
in Sunday's 9-2 loss to Colorado and have done so only five times
in 52 innings. They have had a 1-2-3 inning only twice in 33
innings. ... The Pirates have not won a game in which they led the
entire way since Aug. 5. ... Pirates RHP Kris Benson threw Sunday
as scheduled and will start Tuesday against the Giants. The start
was moved back two days so Benson could rest a tired arm. He is
winless since July 8. ... OF Brian Giles failed to get a hit Sunday
for only the second time in 14 games. ... Of the mounting criticism
of the now last-place Pirates, general manager Cam Bonifay said,
''It's very bothering to me that we've had the type of year we've
had. People want to say negative things about the things that have
happened this year, and they have the right to do so, but the job
of the general manager is to stay positive and focused.''
Diamondbacks-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Sunday's loss dropped former Mets pitcher Armando
Reynoso to 5-3 against New York. ... Pinch-runner Tony Womack stole
his 37th base in the ninth inning. He was left stranded when Greg
Colbrunn struck out to end the game. ... Jay Bell, who ran over
Mike Piazza at home plate on Saturday night, stole a base against
the Mets catcher in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Mike Hampton, one of baseball's best-hitting pitchers,
took it easy at the plate in his first game since being sidelined
by a cracked rib. Hampton skipped batting practice, then bunted
foul for strike three his first time up. He hit a routine fly ball
in his other at-bat. ''I didn't swing hard. I'm not going to
overswing the rest of the year,'' he said. Hampton, who throws
lefty but bats righty, is 17-for-60 (.283) this season. ''I think
I'll just try to hit it to the right side from now on,'' he said.
... The Mets have won 17 of their last 21 games at Shea Stadium.
... Reliever Armando Benitez struck out two in the ninth inning. In
64 relief appearances this year, he's fanned at least two 29 times.
Giants-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Giants pitchers leads the NL with 11 shutouts and
have yielded the least homers (126). ... Monday's starter Shawn
Estes (12-4, 4.10) is 10-2 with a 3.89 ERA over his last 17 starts.
... RF Ellis Burks wasn't in the starting lineup Sunday. His .350
batting average would rank fourth in the NL, but he doesn't have
enough at-bats to qualify for the race. ... The Giants have been in
first place of the NL West for the last 28 days and their biggest
lead has been 3 1-2 games.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Monday's starter Robert Person ranks fifth in the
NL with a 3.29 ERA and has allowed two-or-less runs in each of his
last three starts. ... LF Pat Burrell is the only rookie with two
grand slams this season. ... C Mike Lieberthal has 10 homers and 49
RBIs in his last 50 games. ... The Phillies have turned 10 double
plays in their last five games and have at least one in 13 of 15
(25 total in that span). ... 1B Travis Lee has reached base safely
in 24 of 26 games since he joined Philadelphia.
Cardinals-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: C Carlos Hernandez sustained a freak back injury
while hitting in the fifth inning. After taking ball four,
Hernandez took a step toward first base but suddenly pulled up, in
obvious pain from a lower back sprain. He walked gingerly off the
field, assisted by a trainer and coach, and was sent back to St.
Louis to get checked by team doctors. ''It might be something that
keeps him out for a while,'' manager Tony La Russa said. ...
Catcher Keith McDonald, playing at Triple-A Memphis, was told to
meet the team in Florida for Monday night's game against the
Marlins in case Hernandez is put on the disabled list. Eli Marrero,
doing an injury rehab assignment at Memphis after tearing a
ligament in his left thumb, should be ready to rejoin the team by
next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: CF Andruw Jones finally got a day off to rest his sore
right hamstring, ending a streak of 301 consecutive games. That was
the second-longest active streak in the majors behind Sammy Sosa's
368. Until Sunday, Jones was the only major leaguer to play every
inning of every game this season. He had not missed a game since
Sept. 15, 1998. Despite the nagging pain, he was in the midst of an
eight-game hitting streak (16-for-40). ... RHP John Burkett, who
didn't get a decision after leaving with a 2-1 lead, was going for
his ninth win, which would have matched his total from each of the
last three seasons. His last time with double-figure victories was
1996, when he posted an 11-12 record with Florida and Texas. ...
Manager Bobby Cox remains tied with Tommy Lasorda at 1,599
victories, 14th-most in baseball history.
Padres-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Trevor Hoffman picked up his 263rd career save out of
301 chances Sunday, tops on the career list of save percentages at
.874. ... RHP Woody Williams is 13-5 since Sept. 3, 1999. ... San
Diego is 15-6 on Sundays. The only other day the Padres have a
winning record is Thursdays (7-5). ... 3B Phil Nevin has reached
base safely via a hit or walk 47 consecutive games since July 3. He
is six games shy of tying Shawn Green's major league-best 53-game
streak earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: John Snyder's 1-2-3 first inning was rare. Entering
Sunday's game, he posted a 10.06 ERA in the first inning of 17
starts this season. ... Snyder retired the first 10 batters he
faced and did not allow a hit until Nevin's single in the fourth.
... Snyder had not won since June 22.
</P>
