<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestininan Hopes to Clear Name  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- An Egyptian-born Palestinian prisoner
who will testify in the Lockerbie bombing trial said in a
television interview broadcast Sunday that he has no information
about the attack and hopes to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Abu Talb, who is serving a life sentence for bombing
American and Jewish targets in Europe, was an early suspect in the
investigations into the Dec. 21, 1988, bombing of Pan Am Flight
103. The attack killed 270 people over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've suffered a lot, and my family has suffered a lot because
of this, so I feel I have to go and tell the world that I'm
innocent, I have nothing to do with this,'' he said in an interview
with Swedish television's TV4 news from a maximum-security prison
just south of Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   The report said police will have to charter an aircraft to take
Abu Talb to the Netherlands, since no commercial airliner is
willing to fly him.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the two Libyan defendants in the Lockerbie trial,
which began on May 3 in the Netherlands, have indicated they would
try to implicate Abu Talb and nine other suspects. They hope to
cast enough doubt on the prosecution's case to win a dismissal. The
prosecution countered by calling him as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Talb, who came to Sweden in 1983, said he has no information
to offer when he testifies on Sept. 7 except to proclaim his
innocence. But, he said, he fears for the safety of his wife and
three children because unspecified terrorist groups may think he
gave information to prosecutors after they called him as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think I have squealed, that I know something I don't
know,'' he said, according to a transcript of the interview
provided to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Talb, who was convicted of terrorism by a Swedish court in
1989, was linked to the Lockerbie bombing after he was sighted in
Malta in the weeks before the bombing and Swedish police found a
diary in his apartment with the date Dec. 21 circled.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb detonated 38 minutes after the New York-bound plane's
takeoff from London's Heathrow airport. The plane started its
journey in Malta, where the defendants worked in the Libyan Arab
Airlines offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan defendants, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen
Khalifa Fhimah, have pleaded innocent. They blame Palestinian
terrorists operating in Germany at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being conducted by a special Scottish court sitting
at Camp Zeist, a former U.S. air base about 50 miles east of The
Hague.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 2147 </TRAILER>
