<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Costa Rica Plane Crash Kills 10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Rescuers confirmed Sunday that all 10 people on
board a small plane that slammed into a volcano in northern Costa Rica were
killed, airline officials said. Three Americans were among the dead. About 200
rescue workers who climbed the lava-and rock-littered side of Arenal volcano
found the wreckage of the 15-seat, single-engine Cessna Grand Caravan plane,
owned by National Aerial Services, or Sansa. The plane had gone down Saturday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lockerbie Witness Tries To Clear Name
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- An Egyptian-born Palestinian prisoner who will
testify in the Lockerbie bombing trial said in a television interview broadcast
Sunday that he has no information about the attack and hopes to clear his name.
Mohammed Abu Talb, who is serving a life sentence for bombing American and
Jewish targets in Europe, was an early suspect in the investigations into the
Dec. 21, 1988, bombing of Pan Am Flight 103. The attack killed 270 people over
Lockerbie, Scotland. ''I'm innocent, I have nothing to do with this,'' he said
in an interview with Swedish television's TV4 news.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
At Least 17 Die in Colombia Massacres
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Gunmen killed at least 17 people in two separate
massacres Sunday, one of which officials attributed to right-wing paramilitary
militias. The killings come three days before President Clinton is to visit
Colombia to discuss U.S. anti-narcotics aid to the drug-producing nation. In one
attack, gunmen seized, interrogated and then executed 10 residents of two poor
neighborhoods in the Caribbean coastal town of Cienaga, Magadalena State police
told The Associated Press.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Illegal Immigrants Riot in Australia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- Illegal immigrants angry that their applications
to stay in Australia were refused rampaged through a detention center, torching
buildings and throwing rocks at staff, authorities said Monday. Up to 80
immigrants were involved in the rioting. ''One canister of tear gas was used to
quell a group of people who were intent on stoning buildings, throwing rocks and
implements at the staff of the center,'' Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock
said. The Woomera detention center houses about 800 illegal immigrants, many of
them from Mideast countries, including Iraq and Afghanistan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
TV Tower Fire Traps 4 in Moscow
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Fire spread relentlessly through the Ostankino television
tower, the world's second-tallest freestanding structure, and blazed into the
early morning Monday as hopes faded for four people believed trapped in an
elevator hundreds of feet above the ground. More than 12 hours after the fire
broke out in the upper reaches of the 1,771-foot futuristic tower, flames had
spread down to about 380 feet above the base. The fire, which began Sunday
afternoon, cut almost all television service in Moscow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Highlights AIDS Assistance
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) -- Africans must ''break the silence'' about AIDS or risk
losing hard-fought democratic and economic gains, President Clinton said Sunday
after touring a health center in the Nigerian capital and hearing the stories of
several people living with the disease. AIDS killed 2.8 million people worldwide
last year, and is now the leading cause of death in Africa. The Clinton
administration will spend $9.4 million this year for AIDS and HIV infection
prevention and care in Nigeria.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Winds Could Worsen Western Fires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Firefighters were on their guard today as 30 mph wind
gusts threatened to worsen wildfires that have turned hundreds of thousands of
acres of forest to ash. Wind already was blamed for whipping up a firestorm in
South Dakota's mountainous Black Hills. The fire had swept across more than
90,000 acres by today, and Forest Service officials said they feared it could
remain explosive. More than ten thousand people were still fighting 23 major
fires in Montana that had charred some 670,000 acres.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped early Monday in light trading, while the
dollar was lower against the yen. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei shed 24.12
points, or 0.14 percent, to 16,887.21 points in early trading. On Friday, the
average closed up 240.51 points, or 1.44 percent. The dollar bought 106.76 yen,
down 0.26 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level
of 107.04 yen on Friday. The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index was down 3.85
points, or 0.25 percent, to 1,527.43 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woods Wins NEC Invitational
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Tiger Woods cruised to another landslide victory at the
NEC Invitational today, this time by 10 strokes. In a fitting conclusion, his
wedge into the 18th green emerged from the darkness and dropped 2 feet from the
hole. Even in overwhelming victory, Woods can still put on a show.
</P>
