<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bridge Collapses in Southern Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A main bridge in southern Taiwan collapsed
Sunday, sending drivers and passengers fleeing their cars and
racing to safety as chunks of concrete dropped into the water
below.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed, but 22 people were taken to hospitals after
330 feet of the Kaohsiung-Pingtung bridge collapsed. The injured
were in stable condition with sprains and cuts, firefighters and
paramedics said.
</P>
<P>
   No cars were found in the river after four hours of searching
with divers, boats and a helicopter, said Lee Ching-pin, a fire
official from Pingtung.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses described a rumbling sound as the four-lane bridge
broke and concrete fell into the river. Cars crashed against the
railings and more than a dozen hung precariously on the tilting
span.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident was under investigation. President
Chen Shui-bian ordered authorities to determine whether shoddy
construction was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Kaohsiung, Taiwan's second-largest city, is about 120 miles
south of the capital, Taipei. The 1.2-mile bridge is the main
thoroughfare into Kaohsiung from neighboring Pingtung county.
</P>
<P>
   Public works and infrastructure in Taiwan have come under fire
since a massive earthquake last year that killed about 2,400
people. The earthquake revealed many buildings to have been
constructed with shoddy materials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
