<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-27 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McKinnon Criticizes Pakistan Army  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Commonwealth Secretary-General Don
McKinnon called Pakistan's military regime unacceptable Sunday and
demanded a quick return to democracy in this impoverished South
Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The attitude of the Commonwealth remains the same. We still do
not see any acceptability to the military regime,'' McKinnon told a
news conference in the capital, Islamabad, at the end of a two-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth, an association comprising Britain and its
former colonies, suspended Pakistan's membership after the Oct. 12
military coup that ousted the government of Nawaz Sharif. Since
then, it has been pressing the military to hold early elections.
</P>
<P>
   But military ruler Gen. Pervez Musharraf says elections will be
held in line with a Supreme Court deadline of three years, not
before. In the meantime, Musharraf says, his government will try to
revive the economy, weed out the corrupt and impose electoral
reforms that will allow for free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   There is little pressure from Pakistanis for elections in a
country where the army has ruled for 25 years of its 53-year
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-27-00 2313 </TRAILER>
